{"title_page": "Jack Driscoll (American football)", "text_new": "{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name            =Jack Driscoll\n| image           =\n| image_size      = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| current_team    = Philadelphia Eagles\n| number          = \n| position        = [[Guard (American and Canadian football)|Offensive guard]]\n| birth_date      = \n| birth_place     = \n| death_date      =  \n| death_place     = \n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=5\n|weight_lb=306\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          = 4\n| draftpick           = 145\n|high_school=\n| college         = [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]]\n| pastteams       =\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status          = \n| highlights      = \n| statleague          = NFL\n| statseason          = \n| statweek            = \n| statlabel1          = \n| statvalue1          = \n| statlabel2          = \n| statvalue2          = \n| nflnew          = \n|pfr=\n}}\nJack Driscoll is an [[American football]] guard for the [[Philadelphia Eagles]].\n\n==College career==\nDriscoll played college football at UMass before transferring to Auburn.<ref>https://www.masslive.com/patriots/2020/04/nfl-draft-2020-former-umass-ol-jack-driscoll-transferred-to-auburn-and-turned-himself-into-a-likely-mid-round-pick.html</ref><ref>https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/sports/college/auburn/2020/04/21/jack-driscoll-nfl-draft-auburn-offensive-tackle-verge-completing-journey-from-two-star-recruit-umass/5168509002/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Philadelphia Eagles roster navbox}}\n{{Eagles2020DraftPicks}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Auburn Tigers football players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Eagles players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name            =Jack Driscoll\n| image           =\n| image_size      = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| current_team    = Philadelphia Eagles\n| number          = \n| position        = [[Guard (American and Canadian football)|Offensive guard]]\n| birth_date      = \n| birth_place     = \n| death_date      =  \n| death_place     = \n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=5\n|weight_lb=306\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          = 4\n| draftpick           = 145\n|high_school=\n| college         = [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]]\n| pastteams       =\n* [[Philadelphia Eagles]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status          = \n| highlights      = \n| statleague          = NFL\n| statseason          = \n| statweek            = \n| statlabel1          = \n| statvalue1          = \n| statlabel2          = \n| statvalue2          = \n| nflnew          = \n|pfr=\n}}\nJack Driscoll is an [[American football]] guard for the [[Philadelphia Eagles]].\n\n==College career==\nDriscoll played college football at UMass before transferring to Auburn.<ref>https://www.masslive.com/patriots/2020/04/nfl-draft-2020-former-umass-ol-jack-driscoll-transferred-to-auburn-and-turned-himself-into-a-likely-mid-round-pick.html</ref><ref>https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/sports/college/auburn/2020/04/21/jack-driscoll-nfl-draft-auburn-offensive-tackle-verge-completing-journey-from-two-star-recruit-umass/5168509002/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Philadelphia Eagles players]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Driscoll_(American_football)"}
{"title_page": "Kathrine Switzer", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{short description|German-born American runner}}\n{{Infobox person/Wikidata\n| name         = Kathrine Switzer\n| image        = Kathrine Switzer at the 2011 Berlin Marathon Expo.jpg\n| caption      = Kathrine Switzer at the 2011 [[Berlin Marathon]] expo\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1947|1|5}}\n| birth_place  = [[Amberg]], Germany\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| height       = \n| occupation   = Runner and author\n| years_active = \n| salary       =\n| alma_mater   = [[Syracuse University]]\n| education    = [[George C. Marshall High School]]\n| spouse       = Tom Miller (1968\u20131973)<br>Philip Schaub<br>Roger Robinson (m. 1987)\n| networth     =\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.kathrineswitzer.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Kathrine Virginia Switzer''' (born January 5, 1947, in [[Amberg]], Germany)<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.germanroadraces.de/274-1-16454-kathrine-switzer-and-roger-robinson-visit-the.html |title = Kathrine Switzer and Roger Robinson visit the Berlin Sports Museum |last = Milde |first = Horst |date = June 2, 2010 |work = German Road Races e.V. |accessdate = March 19, 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140308220723/http://www.germanroadraces.de/274-1-16454-kathrine-switzer-and-roger-robinson-visit-the.html |archive-date = March 8, 2014 |url-status = dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref> is an American marathon runner, author, and television commentator.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.espn.com/espnw/news-commentary/story/_/id/7803502/2012-boston-marathon-how-kathrine-switzer-paved-way-female-runners |title = How Kathrine Switzer paved the way |last = Lorge Butler |first = Sarah |date = April 12, 2012 |work = ESPN |accessdate = July 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1967, she became the first woman to run the [[Boston Marathon#History|Boston Marathon]] as a numbered entrant. During her run, race manager [[Jock Semple]] repeatedly assaulted Switzer trying to grab her [[bib number]] and stop her competing.  After knocking down Switzer's trainer and fellow runner Arnie Briggs when he tried to protect her, Semple was shoved to the ground by Switzer's boyfriend, Thomas Miller, who was running with her, and she completed the race.<ref name =\"KS Life\"/> Women were banned from competing in races against men as a result of her run, and it was not until 1972 that the Boston Marathon established an official women's race.<ref name=\"Impowerage\">{{cite news |last = Lodge |first = Denise |url = http://impowerage.com/not-too-late/active/kathrine-switzer-empowerment-through-running |title = Kathrine Switzer: Empowerment through Running |work = Impowerage Magazine |date = April 16, 2012 |access-date = May 10, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nKathrine Switzer was born in Amberg, Germany, the daughter of a major in the [[United States Army]]. Her family returned to the United States in 1949.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.germanroadraces.de/274-0-27111-katherine-switzer-65-jahre-gratulation-der.html |title = Katherine Switzer 65 Jahre - GRATULATION der Laufpionierin! |last = Milde |first = Horst |date = January 5, 2012 |language = de |work = German Road Races e.V. |accessdate = March 19, 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140329011408/http://www.germanroadraces.de/274-0-27111-katherine-switzer-65-jahre-gratulation-der.html |archive-date = March 29, 2014 |url-status = dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref> She graduated from [[George C. Marshall High School]] in [[Fairfax County, Virginia]], then attended [[Lynchburg College]].<ref name=\"tomd\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bostonmarathonfi00derd/page/302|title=Boston Marathon : the first century of the world's premier running event|last=1949-|first=Derderian, Tom|date=1996|page=[https://archive.org/details/bostonmarathonfi00derd/page/302 302]|publisher=Human Kinetics|isbn=0880114797|location=Champaign, IL|oclc=33160969|url-access=registration}}</ref> She transferred to [[Syracuse University]] in 1967, where she studied journalism and English literature.<ref name=\"lady\">{{cite web |url = http://www.mediaed.org/assets/products/151/Kathy_Switzer.pdf |title = Lady With Desire to Run Crashed Marathon |date = April 23, 1967 |work = The New York Times |accessdate = November 2, 2014 |format = pdf |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120306124858/http://www.mediaed.org/assets/products/151/Kathy_Switzer.pdf |archivedate = March 6, 2012 |df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"tomd\" /> She earned a bachelor's degree there in 1968 and a master's degree in 1972.\n\n===1967 Boston Marathon===\nAfter her 50 year old coach Arnie Briggs insisted a marathon was too far to run for a \"fragile woman\",<ref>{{cite news\n |url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-08-22/women-shine-as-gender-barriers-continue-to-fall-us-army-rangers/6716888\n |date = August 22, 2015\n |publisher = Australian Broadcasting Commission\n |title = First women graduate from US Army Ranger School as gender barriers continue to fall\n |first = Jennifer\n |last = King\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150822132200/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-08-22/women-shine-as-gender-barriers-continue-to-fall-us-army-rangers/6716888\n |archivedate = August 22, 2015 }}</ref> he conceded that 'If any woman could do it, you could, but you would have to prove it to me. If you ran the distance in practice, I\u2019d be the first to take you to Boston'.<ref name =\"KS Life\"/> Switzer trained with him for the 1967 Boston Marathon which she completed under entry number 261 as a member of the Syracuse Harriers athletic club.<ref name=\"lady\" /> As a result of her run, the [[Amateur Athletic Union|Amateur Athletic Union (AAU)]] barred women from taking part in races with men:<ref name=romanelli /> it took five more years before the Boston Marathon ran its first official women's race. Her finishing time of approximately 4 hours and 20 minutes was nearly an hour behind the first female finisher, [[Bobbi Gibb]], who ran unregistered.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.coolrunning.com/boston/results2.htm |title = BAA Marathon Results |publisher = }}</ref> Having checked that the rule book for the marathon made no mention of gender, she registered for the race using her official AAU number, the full race fee, a properly acquired certificate of fitness, and with the form 'signed as I always sign my name, ''K.V. Switzer'' '.<ref name =\"KS Life\">\n{{cite book\n |last=Switzer\n |first=Kathrine\n |author-link=\n |date=2017-04-04\n |access-date=2020-04-24\n |edition=4th\n |title=Marathon Woman\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420232514/https://kathrineswitzer.com/1967-boston-marathon-the-real-story/\n |archive-date=2020-04-20\n |url=https://kathrineswitzer.com/1967-boston-marathon-the-real-story/\n |url-status=live\n |location=\n |publisher=Da Capo Press Inc\n |isbn=0306825651\n|quote=We checked the rule book and entry form; there was nothing about gender in the marathon. I filled in my AAU number, plunked down $3 cash as entry fee, signed as I always sign my name, 'K.V. Switzer,' and went to the university infirmary to get a fitness certificate.\n}}</ref> She also stated that her name had been misspelled on her birth certificate, so she often used her initials to avoid confusion.<ref>{{cite news\n |url = http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/17/us/boston-marathon-kathrine-switzer-trnd/index.html\n |title = 1st woman to officially run Boston Marathon to do it again 50 years later\n |last = Grinberg\n |first = Emanuella\n |publisher = CNN\n |access-date = April 17, 2017 }}</ref>\nSwitzer's father was supportive of his daughter's entry into the race, and on race day other runners assembling for the start greeted her entry into the race with support and enthusiasm, leading her to feel 'very welcome'.<ref name =\"KS Life\"/>\n\nHowever, race officials opposed women competing in the marathon, and photographs of race manager [[Jock Semple]] attempting to rip Switzer's number off were widespread in the media.<ref name=\"SI_AngryOverseer\">{{cite web\n |url = https://www.si.com/vault/1968/04/22/609806/angry-overseer-of-the-marathon\n |title = Angry Overseer Of The Marathon\n |work = Sports Illustrated\n |first = Myron\n |last = Cope\n |date = April 22, 1968\n |accessdate = December 5, 2012 }}</ref> \n\nSemple repeatedly assaulted Switzer during the race in an attempt to remove her race number and prevent her continuing to compete<ref name =\"KS Life\"/> while shouting, \"Get the hell out of my race and give me those numbers!\"<ref name=\"Concannon\">\n{{cite news \n|last = Concannon\n |first = Joe\n |date = April 5, 1987\n |url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/59480176.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current\n |title = 1967: Semple Meets Switzer. Versions vary but everyone remembers that infamous marathon\n |work = [[Boston Globe]] }}\n</ref>\nSemple knocked down Switzer's coach and fellow competitor, Arnie Briggs, when Briggs attempted to protect Switzer.<ref name=\"KS Life\" />\nSemple succeeded in removing one of Switzer's gloves and only stopped his attacks when Switzer's then-boyfriend Tom Miller, a 235-pound ex-football player and nationally ranked [[hammer throw]]er who was running with her, knocked Semple to the ground.<ref name =\"KS Life\"/><ref name = \"Runners Icon\">\n{{cite web \n|url = https://kathrineswitzer.com/wp-content/uploads/womens-running.pdf \n|title = Womens Running Icon 7 \n| work = Runner's World }}\n</ref><ref name=\"ESPN\">\n{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.espn.com/espnw/news-commentary/article/7803502/2012-boston-marathon-how-kathrine-switzer-paved-way-female-runners\n| title      = How Kathrine Switzer paved the way\n| author     = Sarah Lorge Butler\n| work       = ESPNW\n| date       = 2012-04-12\n| accessdate = 2017-03-27\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.runnersworld.com/runners-stories/kathrine-switzer-runs-the-boston-marathon\n| title      = The Girl Who Started It All\n| work       = Runner's World\n| date       = 2007-03-06\n| accessdate = 2017-03-27\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url        = https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-17632029\n| title      = Boston, 1967: When marathons were just for men\n| author     = Kathrine Switzer\n| work       = BBC\n| date       = 2012-04-16\n| accessdate = 2017-03-27\n}}</ref> Photographs taken of the incident made world headlines.<ref name=\"KS Life\" /><ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fE2gQr7GYJE |title = MAKERS: Women Who Make America (Ep1) Awakening - PBS America |first =  |last = PBSAmerica |date = August 15, 2013 |publisher =  |via = YouTube }}</ref>\n\nDespite the rule book making no mention of gender,<ref name =\"KS Life\"/> Semple later claimed that Switzer was issued a number through an \"oversight\" in the entry screening process, and was treated as an interloper when the supposed 'error' was discovered.<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Semple |first = Jock |first2 = John J. |last2 = Kelley |first3 = Tom |last3 = Murphy |year = 1981 |title = Just Call Me Jock: The Story of Jock Semple, Boston's Mr. Marathon |pages = [https://archive.org/details/justcallmejockst0000semp/page/7 7, 114\u2013118] |publisher = Waterford Publishing |isbn = 978-0942052015 |url = https://archive.org/details/justcallmejockst0000semp/page/7 }}</ref>\n\nAfterward, [[Boston Athletic Association]] director Will Cloney was asked his opinion of Switzer competing in the race. Although the race rule book made no mention of gender and Switzer had a properly issued valid race registration<ref name =\"KS Life\"/> Cloney said, \"Women can't run in the Marathon because the rules forbid it. Unless we have rules, society will be in chaos. I don't make the rules, but I try to carry them out. We have no space in the Marathon for any unauthorized person, even a man. If that girl were my daughter, I would spank her.\"<ref name=\"lady\" />\n\nBecause of her run, the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) barred women from all competitions with male runners, with violators losing the right to compete in any races.<ref name=romanelli>\n{{cite book\n |title = The Women's Book of World Records and Achievements\n |url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_0385127332\n |url-access = registration\n |last = Romanelli\n |first = Elaine\n |editor-last = O'Neill\n |editor-first = Lois Decker\n |publisher = Anchor Press\n |year = 1979 |page = [https://archive.org/details/isbn_0385127332/page/576 576]\n |chapter = Women in Sports and Games |isbn = 0-385-12733-2 }}\n</ref> Switzer, with other women runners, tried to convince the Boston Athletic Association to allow women to participate in the marathon. Finally, in 1972, the Boston Marathon established an official women's race.<ref name=\"Impowerage\" />\n\nAccording to Switzer, she understood the gravity of her participation and accomplishment:\n\n{{quote frame|text=I knew if I quit, nobody would ever believe that women had the capability to run 26-plus miles. If I quit, everybody would say it was a publicity stunt. If I quit, it would set women's sports back, way back, instead of forward. If I quit, I'd never run Boston. If I quit, Jock Semple and all those like him would win. My fear and humiliation turned to anger.<ref name=\"KS Life\" />}}\n\n===Later competition, work, and honors===\n\nSwitzer was the women's winner of the 1974 [[New York City Marathon]], with a time of 3:07:29 (59th overall).<ref name=MW2007A>{{cite book |last = Switzer |first = Kathrine |title = Marathon Woman |publisher = Carroll & Graf |location = New York |year = 2007 |page = 270 |isbn = 978-0-7867-1967-9 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.nyrr.org |title = Home |date = March 26, 2012 |publisher = }}</ref> Her personal best time for the marathon distance is 2:51:37, at Boston in 1975.<ref name=MW2007B>{{cite book |last = Switzer |first = Kathrine |title = Marathon Woman |publisher = Carroll & Graf |location = New York |year = 2007 |page = 290 |isbn = 978-0-7867-1967-9 }}</ref>\n\nSwitzer was named Female Runner of the Decade (1967\u201377) by ''[[Runner's World Magazine]]'' and later became a television commentator for marathons, starting with the 1984 Olympic women's marathon, and received an Emmy for her work.<ref name=\"Impowerage\" /><ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-state-of-nova/post/kathrine-switzer-boston-marathon-pioneer-started-running-in-fairfax-county-went-to-marshall-hs/2012/09/23/f1d80d12-0406-11e2-8102-ebee9c66e190_blog.html |title = Kathrine Switzer, Boston Marathon women's pioneer, started running in Dunn Loring, went to Marshall HS |author = Tom Jackman |work = Washington Post |date = September 23, 2012 |accessdate = March 27, 2017 }}</ref> In 1979, the [[Supersisters]] trading card set was produced and distributed; one of the cards featured Switzer's name and picture.<ref>{{cite web |last = Wulf |first = Steve |url = http://espn.go.com/espnw/news-commentary/article/12535055/original-roster |title = Supersisters: Original Roster |publisher = ESPN |date = March 23, 2015 |accessdate = June 4, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nShe wrote ''Running and Walking for Women over 40'' in 1997. She released her memoir, ''Marathon Woman'', in April 2007, on the 40th anniversary of her first running of the Boston Marathon. In April 2008, ''Marathon Woman'' won the [[Billie Awards|Billie Award]] for journalism for its inspiring portrayal of women in sports.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://kathrineswitzer.com/author/books/ |title = Kathrine Switzer Website |accessdate = April 15, 2014 }}</ref>  When visiting the Boston Marathon, Switzer is glad to see other female runners:\n\n{{quote|text=When I go to the Boston Marathon now, I have wet shoulders\u2014women fall into my arms crying. They're weeping for joy because running has changed their lives. They feel they can do anything.|author=Kathrine Switzer |source=The Nation (2013)<ref name=tears-love>{{cite journal|last=Zirin |first=Dave |title=The Boston Marathon: All My Tears, All My Love |journal=[[The Nation]] |date=April 15, 2013 |url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/173851/boston-marathon-all-my-tears-all-my-love |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115100141/https://www.thenation.com/article/boston-marathon-all-my-tears-all-my-love/ |archive-date=January 15, 2016 }}</ref>}}\n\nShe was inducted into the [[National Women's Hall of Fame]] in 2011 for creating a social revolution by empowering women around the world through running.<ref name=\"Impowerage\" /> Since 1967, she has worked to improve running opportunities for women in different parts of the world.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-17632029 |publisher = BBC News |date = April 16, 2012 |title = Boston, 1967: When marathons were just for men |accessdate = May 1, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Kathrine Switzer launched her global non-profit 261 Fearless with an ambassador program, club training system and events. 261 Fearless uses running as the means to empower women to overcome life obstacles and embrace healthy living.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.runningusa.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=news.details&ArticleId=4269 |publisher = Running USA |date = October 20, 2015 |title = Kathrine Switzer Launches Global Non-Profit 261 Fearless, Inc. with an Ambassador Program, Club Training System and Events |accessdate = May 17, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.261fearless.org/about-261 |title = About 261 Fearless  |publisher = 261 Fearless|accessdate = May 17, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nFor the 2017 Boston Marathon, bib number 261, the same number Switzer was assigned in 1967, was assigned to her as  \"Switzer, Kathrine V.\" This marked the 50th anniversary of her historic marathon. She was placed in wave 1 and corral 1 and finished in 4:44:31.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://registration.baa.org/2017/cf/Public/iframe_EntryLists.cfm |title = B.A.A. Marathon 2017: Entry List |publisher = }}</ref> Also in 2017, the [[Boston Athletic Association]] announced it would not assign bib number 261 to any future runners, as an honor for Switzer.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.miamiherald.com/latest-news/article144470079.html#storylink=cpy |title = Boston Marathon retires Bib No. 261 for women's pioneer |work = Miami Herald }}</ref> It was her ninth Boston Marathon. She was leading a team of runners from her nonprofit, 261 Fearless, Inc., which she hopes will connect and empower women through running. And rather than being the only official woman in the race like in 1967, she was joined by over 13,700 women\u2014almost half of the total runners.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.newsweek.com/boston-marathon-kathrine-switzer-261-fearless-symbol-women-running-584645 |publisher = Newsweek |date = April 16, 2017 |title = The Boston Marathon: How Kathrine Switzer's 261 Became a Symbol for Women in Sports |accessdate = May 17, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2017, she ran the [[New York City Marathon]], which marked the first time she had run it since 1974; she finished in 4:48:21.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/kevin-hart-gets-serious-beats-tiki-barber-in-nyc-marathon/2017/11/05/6f321048-c287-11e7-9922-4151f5ca6168_story.html|title=Kevin Hart gets serious, beats Tiki Barber in NYC Marathon|website=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Switzer was the commencement speaker at the 164<sup>th</sup> commencement of [[Syracuse University]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2018/03/kathrine_switzer_picked_to_be_syracuse_university_commencement_speaker.html|title=Kathrine Switzer picked to be Syracuse University commencement speaker|work=syracuse.com|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.syr.edu/2018/05/all-the-details-on-commencement-2018/|title=All the Details on Commencement 2018|work=SU News|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en-US}}</ref> and received an honorary [[Doctor of humane letters|doctorate of humane letters]] degree.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.syr.edu/2018/04/three-to-receive-honorary-degrees-at-2018-commencement/|title=Three to Receive Honorary Degrees at 2018 Commencement|work=SU News|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1968, Switzer married Tom Miller, the man who had shoved officials for her while running the Boston Marathon in 1967. They divorced in 1973. Switzer married and divorced public relations executive Philip Schaub.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://people.com/archive/when-avon-called-kathy-switzer-gave-up-the-marathon-to-organize-womens-racing-vol-11-no-21/ |title = When Avon Called, Kathy Switzer Gave Up the Marathon to Organize Women's Racing |work = [[People Magazine]] |date = May 28, 1979 }}</ref>  She later married British-born runner and author Roger Robinson in 1987.<ref name=MW2007C>{{cite book |last = Switzer |first = Kathrine |title = Marathon Woman |publisher = Carroll & Graf |location = New York |year = 2007 |pages = 132\u201333, 203\u201304, 382\u201383 |isbn = 978-0-7867-1967-9 }}</ref><ref name=\"Lynch\">{{cite web |url = http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-love-story-switzer-robinson-0928-20140919-story.html |title = Legendary Runners Slow Down Long Enough To Marry |last = Lynch |first = M.A.C. |date = September 30, 2014 |accessdate = August 22, 2015 |url-access=registration  }}</ref>\n\n==Achievements==\n{| {{AchievementTable}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"|Representing the {{USA}}\n|-\n|1974\n|[[New York City Marathon]]\n|New York, United States\n|bgcolor=\"blue\" | <span style=\"color:#fff;\">1st</span>\n|3:07:29<ref name=MW2007A />\n|-\n|1975\n|[[Boston Marathon]]\n|[[Boston, Massachusetts]], United States\n|bgcolor=\"silver\"  | 2nd\n|2:51:37<ref name=MW2007B />\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.katherineswitzer.com Kathrine Switzer website]\n* [http://www.261fearless.org Kathrine Switzer Non Profit Organisation 261 Fearless]\n* [http://www.gettyimages.com/license/515108138 Bettman Archives image of Semple and Switzer at the 1973 Boston Marathon]\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1141740 Marathon Women] - ''[[Morning Edition]]'', [[National Public Radio|NPR]] (April 15, 2002)\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/athletemovie/3112655036/in/set-72157611313252644 Interview with \"ATHLETE\" (film) director David Lam]\n* [http://www.makers.com/kathrine-switzer Kathrine Switzer] Documentary produced by ''[[Makers: Women Who Make America]]''\n\n{{1998 National Distance Running Hall of Fame inductees}}\n{{Footer New York Marathon Champions Women}}\n{{National Women's Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Switzer, Kathrine}}\n[[Category:American female long-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Boston Marathon]]\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New York City Marathon female winners]]\n[[Category:Sports Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{short description|German-born American runner}}\n{{Infobox person/Wikidata\n| name         = Kathrine Switzer\n| image        = Kathrine Switzer at the 2011 Berlin Marathon Expo.jpg\n| caption      = Kathrine Switzer at the 2011 [[Berlin Marathon]] expo\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1947|1|5}}\n| birth_place  = [[Amberg]], Germany\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| height       = \n| occupation   = Runner and author\n| years_active = \n| salary       =\n| alma_mater   = [[Syracuse University]]\n| education    = [[George C. Marshall High School]]\n| spouse       = Tom Miller (1968\u20131973)<br>Philip Schaub<br>Roger Robinson (m. 1987)\n| networth     =\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.kathrineswitzer.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Kathrine Virginia Switzer''' (born January 5, 1947, in [[Amberg]], Germany)<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.germanroadraces.de/274-1-16454-kathrine-switzer-and-roger-robinson-visit-the.html |title = Kathrine Switzer and Roger Robinson visit the Berlin Sports Museum |last = Milde |first = Horst |date = June 2, 2010 |work = German Road Races e.V. |accessdate = March 19, 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140308220723/http://www.germanroadraces.de/274-1-16454-kathrine-switzer-and-roger-robinson-visit-the.html |archive-date = March 8, 2014 |url-status = dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref> is an American marathon runner, author, and television commentator.<ref>{{cite news |url = https://www.espn.com/espnw/news-commentary/story/_/id/7803502/2012-boston-marathon-how-kathrine-switzer-paved-way-female-runners |title = How Kathrine Switzer paved the way |last = Lorge Butler |first = Sarah |date = April 12, 2012 |work = ESPN |accessdate = July 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1967, she became the first woman to run the [[Boston Marathon#History|Boston Marathon]] as a numbered entrant. During her run, race manager [[Jock Semple]] repeatedly assaulted Switzer trying to grab her [[bib number]] and stop her competing.  After knocking down Switzer's trainer and fellow runner Arnie Briggs when he tried to protect her, Semple was shoved to the ground by Switzer's boyfriend, Thomas Miller, who was running with her, and she completed the race.<ref name =\"KS Life\"/> Women were banned from competing in races against men as a result of her run, and it was was not until 1972 that the Boston Marathon established an official women's race.<ref name=\"Impowerage\">{{cite news |last = Lodge |first = Denise |url = http://impowerage.com/not-too-late/active/kathrine-switzer-empowerment-through-running |title = Kathrine Switzer: Empowerment through Running |work = Impowerage Magazine |date = April 16, 2012 |access-date = May 10, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nKathrine Switzer was born in Amberg, Germany, the daughter of a major in the [[United States Army]]. Her family returned to the United States in 1949.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.germanroadraces.de/274-0-27111-katherine-switzer-65-jahre-gratulation-der.html |title = Katherine Switzer 65 Jahre - GRATULATION der Laufpionierin! |last = Milde |first = Horst |date = January 5, 2012 |language = de |work = German Road Races e.V. |accessdate = March 19, 2013 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140329011408/http://www.germanroadraces.de/274-0-27111-katherine-switzer-65-jahre-gratulation-der.html |archive-date = March 29, 2014 |url-status = dead |df = mdy-all }}</ref> She graduated from [[George C. Marshall High School]] in [[Fairfax County, Virginia]], then attended [[Lynchburg College]].<ref name=\"tomd\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bostonmarathonfi00derd/page/302|title=Boston Marathon : the first century of the world's premier running event|last=1949-|first=Derderian, Tom|date=1996|page=[https://archive.org/details/bostonmarathonfi00derd/page/302 302]|publisher=Human Kinetics|isbn=0880114797|location=Champaign, IL|oclc=33160969|url-access=registration}}</ref> She transferred to [[Syracuse University]] in 1967, where she studied journalism and English literature.<ref name=\"lady\">{{cite web |url = http://www.mediaed.org/assets/products/151/Kathy_Switzer.pdf |title = Lady With Desire to Run Crashed Marathon |date = April 23, 1967 |work = The New York Times |accessdate = November 2, 2014 |format = pdf |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120306124858/http://www.mediaed.org/assets/products/151/Kathy_Switzer.pdf |archivedate = March 6, 2012 |df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"tomd\" /> She earned a bachelor's degree there in 1968 and a master's degree in 1972.\n\n===1967 Boston Marathon===\nAfter her 50 year old coach Arnie Briggs insisted a marathon was too far to run for a \"fragile woman\",<ref>{{cite news\n |url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-08-22/women-shine-as-gender-barriers-continue-to-fall-us-army-rangers/6716888\n |date = August 22, 2015\n |publisher = Australian Broadcasting Commission\n |title = First women graduate from US Army Ranger School as gender barriers continue to fall\n |first = Jennifer\n |last = King\n |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150822132200/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-08-22/women-shine-as-gender-barriers-continue-to-fall-us-army-rangers/6716888\n |archivedate = August 22, 2015 }}</ref> he conceded that 'If any woman could do it, you could, but you would have to prove it to me. If you ran the distance in practice, I\u2019d be the first to take you to Boston'.<ref name =\"KS Life\"/> Switzer trained with him for the 1967 Boston Marathon which she completed under entry number 261 as a member of the Syracuse Harriers athletic club.<ref name=\"lady\" /> As a result of her run, the [[Amateur Athletic Union|Amateur Athletic Union (AAU)]] barred women from taking part in races with men:<ref name=romanelli /> it took five more years before the Boston Marathon ran its first official women's race. Her finishing time of approximately 4 hours and 20 minutes was nearly an hour behind the first female finisher, [[Bobbi Gibb]], who ran unregistered.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.coolrunning.com/boston/results2.htm |title = BAA Marathon Results |publisher = }}</ref> Having checked that the rule book for the marathon made no mention of gender, she registered for the race using her official AAU number, the full race fee, a properly acquired certificate of fitness, and with the form 'signed as I always sign my name, ''K.V. Switzer'' '.<ref name =\"KS Life\">\n{{cite book\n |last=Switzer\n |first=Kathrine\n |author-link=\n |date=2017-04-04\n |access-date=2020-04-24\n |edition=4th\n |title=Marathon Woman\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420232514/https://kathrineswitzer.com/1967-boston-marathon-the-real-story/\n |archive-date=2020-04-20\n |url=https://kathrineswitzer.com/1967-boston-marathon-the-real-story/\n |url-status=live\n |location=\n |publisher=Da Capo Press Inc\n |isbn=0306825651\n|quote=We checked the rule book and entry form; there was nothing about gender in the marathon. I filled in my AAU number, plunked down $3 cash as entry fee, signed as I always sign my name, 'K.V. Switzer,' and went to the university infirmary to get a fitness certificate.\n}}</ref> She also stated that her name had been misspelled on her birth certificate, so she often used her initials to avoid confusion.<ref>{{cite news\n |url = http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/17/us/boston-marathon-kathrine-switzer-trnd/index.html\n |title = 1st woman to officially run Boston Marathon to do it again 50 years later\n |last = Grinberg\n |first = Emanuella\n |publisher = CNN\n |access-date = April 17, 2017 }}</ref>\nSwitzer's father was supportive of his daughter's entry into the race, and on race day other runners assembling for the start greeted her entry into the race with support and enthusiasm, leading her to feel 'very welcome'.<ref name =\"KS Life\"/>\n\nHowever, race officials opposed women competing in the marathon, and photographs of race manager [[Jock Semple]] attempting to rip Switzer's number off were widespread in the media.<ref name=\"SI_AngryOverseer\">{{cite web\n |url = https://www.si.com/vault/1968/04/22/609806/angry-overseer-of-the-marathon\n |title = Angry Overseer Of The Marathon\n |work = Sports Illustrated\n |first = Myron\n |last = Cope\n |date = April 22, 1968\n |accessdate = December 5, 2012 }}</ref> \n\nSemple repeatedly assaulted Switzer during the race in an attempt to remove her race number and prevent her continuing to compete<ref name =\"KS Life\"/> while shouting, \"Get the hell out of my race and give me those numbers!\"<ref name=\"Concannon\">\n{{cite news \n|last = Concannon\n |first = Joe\n |date = April 5, 1987\n |url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/59480176.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current\n |title = 1967: Semple Meets Switzer. Versions vary but everyone remembers that infamous marathon\n |work = [[Boston Globe]] }}\n</ref>\nSemple knocked down Switzer's coach and fellow competitor, Arnie Briggs, when Briggs attempted to protect Switzer.<ref name=\"KS Life\" />\nSemple succeeded in removing one of Switzer's gloves and only stopped his attacks when Switzer's then-boyfriend Tom Miller, a 235-pound ex-football player and nationally ranked [[hammer throw]]er who was running with her, knocked Semple to the ground.<ref name =\"KS Life\"/><ref name = \"Runners Icon\">\n{{cite web \n|url = https://kathrineswitzer.com/wp-content/uploads/womens-running.pdf \n|title = Womens Running Icon 7 \n| work = Runner's World }}\n</ref><ref name=\"ESPN\">\n{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.espn.com/espnw/news-commentary/article/7803502/2012-boston-marathon-how-kathrine-switzer-paved-way-female-runners\n| title      = How Kathrine Switzer paved the way\n| author     = Sarah Lorge Butler\n| work       = ESPNW\n| date       = 2012-04-12\n| accessdate = 2017-03-27\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url        = http://www.runnersworld.com/runners-stories/kathrine-switzer-runs-the-boston-marathon\n| title      = The Girl Who Started It All\n| work       = Runner's World\n| date       = 2007-03-06\n| accessdate = 2017-03-27\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url        = https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-17632029\n| title      = Boston, 1967: When marathons were just for men\n| author     = Kathrine Switzer\n| work       = BBC\n| date       = 2012-04-16\n| accessdate = 2017-03-27\n}}</ref> Photographs taken of the incident made world headlines.<ref name=\"KS Life\" /><ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fE2gQr7GYJE |title = MAKERS: Women Who Make America (Ep1) Awakening - PBS America |first =  |last = PBSAmerica |date = August 15, 2013 |publisher =  |via = YouTube }}</ref>\n\nDespite the rule book making no mention of gender,<ref name =\"KS Life\"/> Semple later claimed that Switzer was issued a number through an \"oversight\" in the entry screening process, and was treated as an interloper when the supposed 'error' was discovered.<ref>\n{{cite book |last = Semple |first = Jock |first2 = John J. |last2 = Kelley |first3 = Tom |last3 = Murphy |year = 1981 |title = Just Call Me Jock: The Story of Jock Semple, Boston's Mr. Marathon |pages = [https://archive.org/details/justcallmejockst0000semp/page/7 7, 114\u2013118] |publisher = Waterford Publishing |isbn = 978-0942052015 |url = https://archive.org/details/justcallmejockst0000semp/page/7 }}</ref>\n\nAfterward, [[Boston Athletic Association]] director Will Cloney was asked his opinion of Switzer competing in the race. Although the race rule book made no mention of gender and Switzer had a properly issued valid race registration<ref name =\"KS Life\"/> Cloney said, \"Women can't run in the Marathon because the rules forbid it. Unless we have rules, society will be in chaos. I don't make the rules, but I try to carry them out. We have no space in the Marathon for any unauthorized person, even a man. If that girl were my daughter, I would spank her.\"<ref name=\"lady\" />\n\nBecause of her run, the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] (AAU) barred women from all competitions with male runners, with violators losing the right to compete in any races.<ref name=romanelli>\n{{cite book\n |title = The Women's Book of World Records and Achievements\n |url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_0385127332\n |url-access = registration\n |last = Romanelli\n |first = Elaine\n |editor-last = O'Neill\n |editor-first = Lois Decker\n |publisher = Anchor Press\n |year = 1979 |page = [https://archive.org/details/isbn_0385127332/page/576 576]\n |chapter = Women in Sports and Games |isbn = 0-385-12733-2 }}\n</ref> Switzer, with other women runners, tried to convince the Boston Athletic Association to allow women to participate in the marathon. Finally, in 1972, the Boston Marathon established an official women's race.<ref name=\"Impowerage\" />\n\nAccording to Switzer, she understood the gravity of her participation and accomplishment:\n\n{{quote frame|text=I knew if I quit, nobody would ever believe that women had the capability to run 26-plus miles. If I quit, everybody would say it was a publicity stunt. If I quit, it would set women's sports back, way back, instead of forward. If I quit, I'd never run Boston. If I quit, Jock Semple and all those like him would win. My fear and humiliation turned to anger.<ref name=\"KS Life\" />}}\n\n===Later competition, work, and honors===\n\nSwitzer was the women's winner of the 1974 [[New York City Marathon]], with a time of 3:07:29 (59th overall).<ref name=MW2007A>{{cite book |last = Switzer |first = Kathrine |title = Marathon Woman |publisher = Carroll & Graf |location = New York |year = 2007 |page = 270 |isbn = 978-0-7867-1967-9 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.nyrr.org |title = Home |date = March 26, 2012 |publisher = }}</ref> Her personal best time for the marathon distance is 2:51:37, at Boston in 1975.<ref name=MW2007B>{{cite book |last = Switzer |first = Kathrine |title = Marathon Woman |publisher = Carroll & Graf |location = New York |year = 2007 |page = 290 |isbn = 978-0-7867-1967-9 }}</ref>\n\nSwitzer was named Female Runner of the Decade (1967\u201377) by ''[[Runner's World Magazine]]'' and later became a television commentator for marathons, starting with the 1984 Olympic women's marathon, and received an Emmy for her work.<ref name=\"Impowerage\" /><ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-state-of-nova/post/kathrine-switzer-boston-marathon-pioneer-started-running-in-fairfax-county-went-to-marshall-hs/2012/09/23/f1d80d12-0406-11e2-8102-ebee9c66e190_blog.html |title = Kathrine Switzer, Boston Marathon women's pioneer, started running in Dunn Loring, went to Marshall HS |author = Tom Jackman |work = Washington Post |date = September 23, 2012 |accessdate = March 27, 2017 }}</ref> In 1979, the [[Supersisters]] trading card set was produced and distributed; one of the cards featured Switzer's name and picture.<ref>{{cite web |last = Wulf |first = Steve |url = http://espn.go.com/espnw/news-commentary/article/12535055/original-roster |title = Supersisters: Original Roster |publisher = ESPN |date = March 23, 2015 |accessdate = June 4, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nShe wrote ''Running and Walking for Women over 40'' in 1997. She released her memoir, ''Marathon Woman'', in April 2007, on the 40th anniversary of her first running of the Boston Marathon. In April 2008, ''Marathon Woman'' won the [[Billie Awards|Billie Award]] for journalism for its inspiring portrayal of women in sports.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://kathrineswitzer.com/author/books/ |title = Kathrine Switzer Website |accessdate = April 15, 2014 }}</ref>  When visiting the Boston Marathon, Switzer is glad to see other female runners:\n\n{{quote|text=When I go to the Boston Marathon now, I have wet shoulders\u2014women fall into my arms crying. They're weeping for joy because running has changed their lives. They feel they can do anything.|author=Kathrine Switzer |source=The Nation (2013)<ref name=tears-love>{{cite journal|last=Zirin |first=Dave |title=The Boston Marathon: All My Tears, All My Love |journal=[[The Nation]] |date=April 15, 2013 |url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/173851/boston-marathon-all-my-tears-all-my-love |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115100141/https://www.thenation.com/article/boston-marathon-all-my-tears-all-my-love/ |archive-date=January 15, 2016 }}</ref>}}\n\nShe was inducted into the [[National Women's Hall of Fame]] in 2011 for creating a social revolution by empowering women around the world through running.<ref name=\"Impowerage\" /> Since 1967, she has worked to improve running opportunities for women in different parts of the world.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-17632029 |publisher = BBC News |date = April 16, 2012 |title = Boston, 1967: When marathons were just for men |accessdate = May 1, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Kathrine Switzer launched her global non-profit 261 Fearless with an ambassador program, club training system and events. 261 Fearless uses running as the means to empower women to overcome life obstacles and embrace healthy living.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.runningusa.org/index.cfm?fuseaction=news.details&ArticleId=4269 |publisher = Running USA |date = October 20, 2015 |title = Kathrine Switzer Launches Global Non-Profit 261 Fearless, Inc. with an Ambassador Program, Club Training System and Events |accessdate = May 17, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.261fearless.org/about-261 |title = About 261 Fearless  |publisher = 261 Fearless|accessdate = May 17, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nFor the 2017 Boston Marathon, bib number 261, the same number Switzer was assigned in 1967, was assigned to her as  \"Switzer, Kathrine V.\" This marked the 50th anniversary of her historic marathon. She was placed in wave 1 and corral 1 and finished in 4:44:31.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://registration.baa.org/2017/cf/Public/iframe_EntryLists.cfm |title = B.A.A. Marathon 2017: Entry List |publisher = }}</ref> Also in 2017, the [[Boston Athletic Association]] announced it would not assign bib number 261 to any future runners, as an honor for Switzer.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.miamiherald.com/latest-news/article144470079.html#storylink=cpy |title = Boston Marathon retires Bib No. 261 for women's pioneer |work = Miami Herald }}</ref> It was her ninth Boston Marathon. She was leading a team of runners from her nonprofit, 261 Fearless, Inc., which she hopes will connect and empower women through running. And rather than being the only official woman in the race like in 1967, she was joined by over 13,700 women\u2014almost half of the total runners.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.newsweek.com/boston-marathon-kathrine-switzer-261-fearless-symbol-women-running-584645 |publisher = Newsweek |date = April 16, 2017 |title = The Boston Marathon: How Kathrine Switzer's 261 Became a Symbol for Women in Sports |accessdate = May 17, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2017, she ran the [[New York City Marathon]], which marked the first time she had run it since 1974; she finished in 4:48:21.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/kevin-hart-gets-serious-beats-tiki-barber-in-nyc-marathon/2017/11/05/6f321048-c287-11e7-9922-4151f5ca6168_story.html|title=Kevin Hart gets serious, beats Tiki Barber in NYC Marathon|website=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Switzer was the commencement speaker at the 164<sup>th</sup> commencement of [[Syracuse University]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2018/03/kathrine_switzer_picked_to_be_syracuse_university_commencement_speaker.html|title=Kathrine Switzer picked to be Syracuse University commencement speaker|work=syracuse.com|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.syr.edu/2018/05/all-the-details-on-commencement-2018/|title=All the Details on Commencement 2018|work=SU News|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en-US}}</ref> and received an honorary [[Doctor of humane letters|doctorate of humane letters]] degree.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.syr.edu/2018/04/three-to-receive-honorary-degrees-at-2018-commencement/|title=Three to Receive Honorary Degrees at 2018 Commencement|work=SU News|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1968, Switzer married Tom Miller, the man who had shoved officials for her while running the Boston Marathon in 1967. They divorced in 1973. Switzer married and divorced public relations executive Philip Schaub.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://people.com/archive/when-avon-called-kathy-switzer-gave-up-the-marathon-to-organize-womens-racing-vol-11-no-21/ |title = When Avon Called, Kathy Switzer Gave Up the Marathon to Organize Women's Racing |work = [[People Magazine]] |date = May 28, 1979 }}</ref>  She later married British-born runner and author Roger Robinson in 1987.<ref name=MW2007C>{{cite book |last = Switzer |first = Kathrine |title = Marathon Woman |publisher = Carroll & Graf |location = New York |year = 2007 |pages = 132\u201333, 203\u201304, 382\u201383 |isbn = 978-0-7867-1967-9 }}</ref><ref name=\"Lynch\">{{cite web |url = http://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-love-story-switzer-robinson-0928-20140919-story.html |title = Legendary Runners Slow Down Long Enough To Marry |last = Lynch |first = M.A.C. |date = September 30, 2014 |accessdate = August 22, 2015 |url-access=registration  }}</ref>\n\n==Achievements==\n{| {{AchievementTable}}\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"|Representing the {{USA}}\n|-\n|1974\n|[[New York City Marathon]]\n|New York, United States\n|bgcolor=\"blue\" | <span style=\"color:#fff;\">1st</span>\n|3:07:29<ref name=MW2007A />\n|-\n|1975\n|[[Boston Marathon]]\n|[[Boston, Massachusetts]], United States\n|bgcolor=\"silver\"  | 2nd\n|2:51:37<ref name=MW2007B />\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.katherineswitzer.com Kathrine Switzer website]\n* [http://www.261fearless.org Kathrine Switzer Non Profit Organisation 261 Fearless]\n* [http://www.gettyimages.com/license/515108138 Bettman Archives image of Semple and Switzer at the 1973 Boston Marathon]\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1141740 Marathon Women] - ''[[Morning Edition]]'', [[National Public Radio|NPR]] (April 15, 2002)\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/athletemovie/3112655036/in/set-72157611313252644 Interview with \"ATHLETE\" (film) director David Lam]\n* [http://www.makers.com/kathrine-switzer Kathrine Switzer] Documentary produced by ''[[Makers: Women Who Make America]]''\n\n{{1998 National Distance Running Hall of Fame inductees}}\n{{Footer New York Marathon Champions Women}}\n{{National Women's Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Switzer, Kathrine}}\n[[Category:American female long-distance runners]]\n[[Category:Boston Marathon]]\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New York City Marathon female winners]]\n[[Category:Sports Emmy Award winners]