orgia]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Seattle Seahawks players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football running back}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = DeeJay Dallas\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| number              = \n| current_team        = Seattle Seahawks\n| position            = [[Running back]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1998|9|16}}\n| birth_place         = [[Brunswick, Georgia]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 5\n| height_in           = 10.5\n| weight_lb           = 217\n| high_school         = [[Glynn Academy]] (Brunswick, GA)\n| college             = [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          = 4\n| draftpick           = 144\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Seattle Seahawks]]  ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Unsigned draft pick\n| highlights          = \n| statleague          = \n| statseason          = \n| statweek            = \n| statlabel1          = \n| statvalue1          = \n| statlabel2          = \n| statvalue2          = \n| statlabel3          = \n| statvalue3          = \n| nfl                 = \n}}\n'''Demetrius \u201cDeeJay\u201d Dallas, Jr.'''(born September 16, 1998) is an [[American football]] [[running back]] for the [[Seattle Seahawks]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]] and was drafted by the Seahawks in the 4th round of the [[2020 NFL Draft]].\n\n== Early years ==\nDallas was born in [[Brunswick, Georgia]] on September 16, 1998. He attended [[Glynn Academy]] in Brunswick, becoming a starter at [[wide receiver]] on the football team in his [[sophomore]] year. He played all over the field while in high school, at wide receiver, running back, [[quarterback]], [[Return specialist|kick returner]], [[Return specialist|punt returner]], and even on defense.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/sports/college/who-deejay-dallas-five-things-know-about-the-miami-freshman-wide-receiver-turned-running-back/zBpZnK4eR3RvPWSTVSaLlI/|title=Who is DeeJay Dallas? Five things to know about the Miami freshman wide receiver turned running back|last=Sydney Hunte|first=Diehards|website=daytondailynews|language=English|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> He was named a first-team all-region 3-5A wide receiver in his sophomore year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/high-school-sports/all-region-teams-stephens-earns-coach-the-year-award-aaaaa/O30xSaNyI0BP2MJgk0FPmL/|title=All-region teams: Stephens earns coach of the year award in 3-AAAAA|last=Todd Holcomb|first=Prep Zone: High School Sports blog|website=ajc|language=english|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>  As a junior, Dallas led Glynn Academy to a Class 5A State Championship appearance for the first time in over 50 years, amassing 678 passing yards, 1,139 rushing yards, 147 receiving yards and 22 total touchdowns over the course of the season and being named region 3-5A player of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jacksonville.com/georgia/2016-12-24/super-24-glynn-academy-s-deejay-dallas-ready-take-miami-challenge|title=Super 24: Glynn Academy's Deejay Dallas ready to take on Miami challenge|last=Freeman|first=Clayton|website=The Florida Times-Union|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebrunswicknews.com/sports/local_sports/all-region-football-team-laden-with-terror-talent/article_caea0fca-cd05-54f5-9ba0-3f544d67e2ae.html|title=All-region football team laden with Terror talent|last=News|first=MICHAEL HALL The Brunswick|website=The Brunswick News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> In his senior season, he amassed 911 passing yards, 1,201 rushing yards, 105 receiving yards, and 24 total touchdowns, while bringing Glynn Academy to the state quarter-finals and being named region 3-5A player of the year again.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebrunswicknews.com/sports/local_sports/glynn-academy-brunswick-fill-up-all-region-football-squads/article_9d132744-2df7-51e0-996e-b45f318d7360.html|title=Glynn Academy, Brunswick fill up all-region football squads|last=tdenman@goldenisles.com|first=TAYLOR DENMAN|website=The Brunswick News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Throughout his high school career, Dallas amassed a total of 1,599 passing yards, 2,502 rushing yards, 779 receiving yards, 430 return yards and 55 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.maxpreps.com/athlete/deejay-dallas/LKtIOSRZEeS00gAmVebEWg/football/stats.htm|title=DeeJay Dallas' High School Football Stats|website=MaxPreps.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Recruiting ===\nDallas was considered one of the top recruits coming out of high school, claiming a spot in the top-300 players of the class of 2017 by [[ESPN]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/football/recruiting/player/_/id/208410/deejay-dallas|title=DeeJay Dallas \u2013 Football Recruiting \u2013 Player Profiles \u2013 ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Because of his versatility on the field, Dallas was listed as an athlete, but most experts thought he would do best as a wide receiver or [[defensive back]]. Most recruiting websites had Dallas as a four-star athlete. Dallas had offers from [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]], [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]], and others, but ultimately chose to play at Miami under head coach [[Mark Richt]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://247sports.com/Player/DeeJay-Dallas-78831/high-school-137102/|title=DeeJay Dallas, Glynn Academy , Athlete|website=247Sports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n{{College athlete recruit start|40=yes|collapse=no|year=2017}}{{College athlete recruit entry|40=4.52|commitdate=May 21, 2016|espn grade=81|recruit=DeeJay Dallas|position=[[Athlete]]|hometown=Brunswick, GA|highschool=Glynn Academy|feet=5|inches=10.5|weight_lbs=191|247 stars=4|rivals stars=4|scout stars=4|espn stars=4}}{{College athlete recruit end|247 overall=12 (ATH), 255 overall|year=2017|epsn archivedate=2017|scout archivedate=2017|rivals archivedate=2017|scout ref title=DeeJay Dallas|scout archiveurl=https://www.scout.com/Player/DeeJay-Dallas-78831/Headlines/|espn archiveurl=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/football/recruiting/school/_/id/2390/class/2017|accessdate=March 18, 2020|247 ref title=Miami 2017 Football Commits|rivals overall=16 (ATH), 196 overall|247 school=miami|247 archiveurl=https://247sports.com/college/miami/Season/2017-Football/Commits/|rivals school=miami|rivals archiveurl=https://miami.rivals.com/commitments/football/2017|rivals ref title=2017 Miami Hurricanes Commitment List|espn ref title=2017 Miami Hurricanes class|espn schoolid=2390|espn overall=16 (ATH), 231 overall|247 archivedate=2017}}\n\n== College career ==\n\n=== Freshman Season ===\nDallas enrolled early at the University of Miami on January 17, 2017. Mark Richt and [[offensive coordinator]] [[Thomas Brown (American football coach)|Thomas Brown]] had him working out at wide receiver through summer camps, as they thought that was his best position, though they were considering moving him to running back. Before the [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2017]] season opener vs. [[2017 Bethune\u2013Cookman Wildcats football team|Bethune-Cookman]], he was listed third on the depth chart at wide receiver.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stateoftheu.com/2017/8/28/16217338/miami-hurricanes-football-depth-chart-for-season-opener-released-malik-rosier-defensive-line-ballers|title=Miami Hurricanes Football: depth chart for season opener released|last=Underwood|first=Cameron J.|date=2017-08-28|website=State of The U|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Dallas saw his first action in the same game, recording a single 16-yard catch. For the next few games, Dallas was not very involved in the game plan, only having a couple kick returns and receptions. After a season-ending injury to starting RB [[Mark Walton (American football)|Mark Walton]], the Hurricanes were in a tough spot because they did not have much depth at the position. Miami looked to Dallas for help, moving him from wide receiver to running back.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-hurricanes/fl-sp-um-football-deejay-dallas-20171115-story.html|title=Freshman DeeJay Dallas making most of his chances with No. 3 Hurricanes|last=Chirinos|first=Christy Cabrera|website=sun-sentinel.com|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> In Week 10, Dallas had a breakout game vs. #3 [[2017 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]]. He had 2 touchdowns and 53 yards rushing on 12 carries, helping the Hurricanes blowout the Fighting Irish 41\u20138. It was only his second week taking meaningful snaps at running back for the Hurricanes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=400934581|title=Notre Dame vs. Miami \u2013 Game Summary \u2013 November 11, 2017 \u2013 ESPN|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Dallas finished strongly that season, totaling 113 rushing yards and 1 touchdown in the [[2017 ACC Championship Game|ACC Championship]] vs. top-ranked [[2017 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson]] and the [[2017 Orange Bowl|Capitol One Orange Bowl]] vs. sixth-ranked [[2017 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caneswarning.com/2018/03/28/miami-hurricanes-rb-deejay-dallas-ready-bigger-role-2018/|title=Miami Hurricanes RB DeeJay Dallas ready for bigger role in 2018|date=2018-03-28|website=Canes Warning|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Dallas finished the season with 217 rushing yards on 41 carries (5.1 {{Abbr|YPC|Yards per Carry}}) and 3 touchdowns, as well as 92 receiving yards on 4 receptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/deejay-dallas-1/gamelog/2017|title=Deejay Dallas 2017 Game Log|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Sophomore Season ===\nDuring the [[offseason]], Dallas' goal was to bulk up to adequate weight for a running back. He was listed at 200 lbs at the start of his freshman season. Head coach Mark Richt said in an interview in the middle of the previous season: \"If he was going to be a running back, he probably would have been 10 pounds heavier.\", although complimenting how well he took on the challenge. Dallas ended up succeeding, as he was listed at 220 lbs by the beginning of his second year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hurricanesports.com/sports/football/roster/deejay-dallas/12403|title=DeeJay Dallas \u2013 Football|website=University of Miami Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> At the beginning of his sophomore campaign, Dallas was the second-string running back on the depth chart, behind standout [[Travis Homer]]. In the season opener vs 25-ranked [[2018 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]], Dallas rushed for a team-high 38 rushing yards on 8 carries (4.8 YPC) in a 33\u201317 loss.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/boxscore?gameId=401013095|title=Miami vs. LSU \u2013 Box Score \u2013 September 2, 2018 \u2013 ESPN|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> He had his first 100-yard collegiate game in Week 3 vs. [[2018 Toledo Rockets football team|Toledo]], where he gained 110 rushing yards on 17 carries (6.5 YPC) and 1 touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=401013114|title=Miami vs. Toledo \u2013 Game Summary \u2013 September 15, 2018 \u2013 ESPN|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Dallas went on to have two more 100-yard games in Week 5 vs. [[2018 North Carolina Tar Heels football team|North Carolina]] and Week 9 vs. [[2018 Duke Blue Devils football team|Duke]]. He also became a reliable special teams returner about halfway through the season, returning it 25 times after Week 5. He even recorded a punt-return touchdown in a Week 12 win over [[2018 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|Pittsburgh.]] While the Hurricanes finished a disappointing 7\u20136 season, Dallas had a solid season as a second-string running back. On the season, he tallied 617 rushing yards on 109 carries (5.7 YPC) and 6 touchdowns, as well as 558 return yards and 1 touchdown. Dallas finished with a team-leading 1260 [[All-purpose yardage|all-purpose]] yards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/deejay-dallas-1/gamelog/2018|title=Deejay Dallas 2018 Game Log|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> He earned 2 team awards in 2018: the Christopher Plumer Memorial Award (Leadership, Motivation, Spirit) and Special Teams MVP.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hurricanesports.com/news/2018/12/15/hurricanes-hold-annual-football-awards-show.aspx|title=Hurricanes Hold Annual Football Awards Show|website=University of Miami Athletics|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Junior Season ===\nAfter the previous season, starting running back Travis Homer declared for the [[2019 NFL Draft]], making Dallas the de facto starter for the Hurricanes in 2019. Head coach Mark Richt stepped down soon after the 2018 season, and the Hurricanes appointed [[defensive coordinator]] [[Manny Diaz (American football)|Manny Diaz]] to fill his place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2813212-report-manny-diaz-hired-as-miami-football-hc-after-mark-richt-retirement|title=Manny Diaz Hired as Miami Football HC After Mark Richt Retirement|last=Zucker|first=Joseph|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Diaz hired [[Dan Enos]] as offensive coordinator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/miami/Article/Miami-announces-the-hiring-of-Dan-Enos-as-OC-127685393/|title=Miami announces the hiring of Dan Enos as OC|website=InsideTheU|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> As Enos had experience with NFL running backs in the past, Dallas had lofty expectations entering his junior season. Most thought his experience in the prior two seasons put him in position for a breakout campaign, especially after recording multiple touchdowns in the Hurricanes' spring game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/miami/Article/Miami-Hurricanes-Spring-Game-2019-QB-Tate-Martell-has-strong-performance-in-Miamis-spring-game-131374662/|title=QB Martell has strong performance in Miami's spring game|website=InsideTheU|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Dallas hit the ground running at the beginning of the season, amassing 309 rushing yards on 35 carries (8.4 YPC) and 4 touchdowns over the first 3 games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stateoftheu.com/2019/9/17/20870725/miami-hurricanes-football-deejay-dallas-running-back-camron-harris-lorenzo-lingard-jarren-williams|title=DeeJay Dallas Off To A Quick Start In 2019|last=marshthomas|date=2019-09-17|website=State of The U|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> However, he did not keep his pace for the rest of the season, averaging only 55 yards per game the following 7 weeks and not hitting the 100-yard mark again, partially due to a nagging knee injury that caused him to miss most of Week 7 vs. [[2019 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football team|Georgia Tech]] and all of Week 8 vs. [[2019 Pittsburgh Panthers football team|Pittsburgh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/sports/college/acc/university-of-miami/article236554823.html|title=The latest updates on statuses of DeeJay Dallas, Jeff Thomas, Michael Pinckney and more|last=Degnan|first=Susan|last2=Wilson|first2=David|date=October 23, 2019|website=Miami Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Dallas' season was cut short by a dislocated elbow injury suffered in Week 10 vs. [[2019 FIU Panthers football team|FIU]]. His injury forced him to miss the final two games of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caneswarning.com/2019/11/27/miami-football-loses-deejay-dallas-for-season-cam-harris-to-first-team/|title=Miami football loses DeeJay Dallas for season, Cam Harris to first team|date=2019-11-27|website=Canes Warning|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> Dallas finished the season with 693 rushing yards on 115 carries (6.0 YPC) and 8 touchdowns, as well 140 receiving yards and 2 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/deejay-dallas-1/gamelog/2019|title=Deejay Dallas 2019 Game Log|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> All of his rushing stats were career highs. Dallas was awarded two team awards in 2019: the R. Dale Melching Leadership Award and one of the Captains of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caneswarning.com/2019/12/16/making-sense-2019-miami-football-team-awards/|title=Making sense of the 2019 Miami football team awards|date=2019-12-16|website=Canes Warning|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\nOn December 27, 2019, Dallas announced that he would forgo his final year of eligibility to enter the [[2020 NFL Draft]]. He finished his Hurricane career with 1,527 rushing yards on 265 carries (5.8 YPC), 317 receiving yards on 28 receptions, and 20 total touchdowns.\n\n=== College Statistics  ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" |Legend\n|-\n|'''Bold'''\n|Career High\n|}\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"20\" style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Miami Hurricanes|color=white}}\" | DeeJay Dallas\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Team\n! Games\n! colspan=\"5\" | Rushing\n! colspan=\"5\" | Receiving\n! colspan=\"5\" |Returning\n! colspan=\"2\" | Fumbles\n|-\n! GP \n! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD\n! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD\n!Ret\n!Yds\n!Avg\n!Lng\n!TD\n! FUM !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2017 NCAA Division