tegory:Miami Hurricanes football players]]\n[[Category:People from Brunswick, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Seattle Seahawks players]]\n", "name_user": "Gcjimmerson", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor word change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DeeJay_Dallas"}
{"title_page": "Zimbabwe Broadcasting Corporation", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox broadcasting network\n| network_name =  (ZBC) {{in lang|en}}|\nnetwork_logo = [[File:Zimbabwe Broadcasting Corporation (logo).jpg|150px|Logo of the ZBC]]\n| country      = [[Zimbabwe]]\n| network_type = [[Television network]] <br /> [[Radio network]]\n| available    = National <br /> Worldwide\n| owner        = [[Government of Zimbabwe]]\n| launch_date  = 1963 (as Rhodesian Broadcasting Corporation)\n| past_names   = Rhodesian Broadcasting Corporation, and later <br /> Zimbabwe Rhodesian Broadcasting Corporation\n| website      = http://www.zbc.co.zw\n}}\n\nThe '''Zimbabwe Broadcasting Corporation '''('''ZBC''') is the state-controlled broadcaster in [[Zimbabwe]]. It was established as the '''Rhodesian Broadcasting Corporation''' ('''RBC'''), taking its current name in 1980. Like the RBC before it, the ZBC has been accused of being a [[government mouthpiece]] with no [[editorial independence]].<ref>[http://www.theindependent.co.zw/2012/02/16/muckraker-zbc-has-taken-over-the-rbcs-mantle/ 'MuckRaker: ZBC has taken over the RBC's mantle'], ''[[Zimbabwe Independent]]'', 16 February 2012</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Introduction of radio===\nRadio was first introduced in the then [[Southern Rhodesia]] in 1933, in Belvedere in Salisbury (now [[Harare]]) by [[Imperial Airways]], which was used to provide radio guidance and weather reports.<ref name=\"Wells\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZgptYdAcsOgC&lpg=PA159&dq=zbc%20radio%204&pg=PA159#v=onepage&q&f=false ''World Broadcasting: A Comparative View''], Alan Wells, Greenwood Publishing Group, 1996, pages 157-159</ref> However, it was not until 1941 that the first professional broadcaster was established.<ref name=\"survey\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LJbFniZhtDQC&lpg=PA10&dq=%22Southern%20Rhodesia%22%20%22radio%22%201933&pg=PA10#v=onepage&q=%22Southern%20Rhodesia%22%20%22radio%22%201933&f=false ''Zimbabwe: A Survey''], African Minds, 2009, page 10</ref> This was known as the Central African Broadcasting Service (CABS) and had responsibility for broadcasting in [[Northern Rhodesia]] (now [[Zambia]]) and [[Nyasaland]] (now [[Malawi]]) as well as Southern Rhodesia.<ref name=\"Wells\" />\n\nFollowing the creation of the [[Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland]] in 1953, a new organisation was established on 1 February 1958, known as the Federal Broadcasting Corporation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland (FBC).<ref name=\"handbook\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DnFHAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22Federal+Broadcasting+Corporation+of+Rhodesia+and+Nyasaland%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Federal+Broadcasting+Corporation%22 ''Handbook to the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland''], Rhodesia and Nyasaland, Federal Information Dept, William Vernon Brelsford, Cassell, 1960, page 552</ref> However, CABS continued to operate as a radio station aimed at African audiences.<ref name=\"Wells\" /> When the Federation was dissolved in 1963, the FBC was disbanded, and each territory acquired its own broadcasting service, which in Southern Rhodesia was initially known as the Southern Rhodesian Broadcasting Corporation (SRBC).<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ht7iAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Southern+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&dq=%22Southern+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjjoIrJrILpAhUWSxUIHfP0BCIQ6AEIXjAH ''Guide to Southern Africa''], 1965, page 249</ref> This later became known as the Rhodesian Broadcasting Corporation (RBC).<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4FDjAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Southern+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&dq=%22Southern+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjjoIrJrILpAhUWSxUIHfP0BCIQ6AEIfDAL ''Standard Encyclopaedia of Southern Africa''], Volume 10, NASOU, 1974, page 132</ref>\n\n===Introduction of television===\n[[ZBC TV| Television]] was introduced on 14 November 1960, first in [[Harare|Salisbury]], with transmissions in [[Bulawayo]] beginning seven months later.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5sZBAQAAIAAJ&dq=rhodesia+television+rtv+1960&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=welensky ''EBU Review: Programmes, Administration, Law, Volume 71''], Administrative Office of the European Broadcasting Union, 1962, page 12</ref> It was only the second such service in sub-Saharan Africa after Nigeria,<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xQBbVfPukGMC&pg=PA32&lpg=PA32&dq=rtv+rhodesia&source=bl&ots=26f1qRRMdU&sig=1yTPAweyK_qpt8hnFGDMLsW4nM0&hl=en&sa=X&ei=zjoYVcHYCcfYPeW1gZgC&ved=0CFkQ6AEwCw#v=onepage&q=rtv%20rhodesia&f=true ''Zimbabwe's Cinematic Arts: Language, Power, Identity''], Katrina Daly Thompson, Indiana University Press, 2013, page 32</ref> and the first such service in southern Africa, as [[South Africa]] did not [[Television in South Africa#Opposition to introduction|introduce television]] until 1976.<ref name=\"Strack\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZVt0AAAAMAAJ&dq=south+africa+TV+1976+rhodesia&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Without+television+until+1976%22 ''Sanctions: The Case of Rhodesia''], Harry R. Strack, Syracuse University Press, 1978,\n page 235</ref>\n\nIt was initially operated by a private company, Rhodesian Television (RTV) on behalf of the then FBC, with its major shareholder being [[South Africa]]n companies, including the [[Cape Argus|Argus Group]] of newspapers, through its subsidiary, the Rhodesian Printing and Publishing Company, and also served [[Northern Rhodesia]] until its independence as [[Zambia]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QadAAAAAIAAJ&dq=Rhodesian%20Television%20(RTV)&pg=PA255#v=onepage&q=Rhodesian%20Television%20(RTV)&f=false ''Area Handbook for Zambia''], Volume 550, Issue 75, Irving Kaplan, American University (Washington, D.C.). Foreign Area Studies\nU.S. Government Printing Office, 1969, page 255</ref> Other companies included Davenport and Meyer,<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HrXVAAAAMAAJ&dq=rhodesia+television+rtv&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22rhodesian+television%22+ ''Viewing the Foreign and the Local in Zimbabwe: Film, Television, and the Shona Viewers''], Katrina Daly Thompson\nUniversity of Wisconsin--Madison, 2004, page 125</ref> the latter of which operated [[LM Radio]], based in [[Mozambique]], then under [[Portuguese Mozambique|Portuguese rule]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G2dmAAAAMAAJ&q=%22davenport+and+meyer%22+lm+radio&dq=%22davenport+and+meyer%22+lm+radio&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiM-JPHwfPKAhXlQpoKHYGHD7oQ6AEIIDAA ''Who's who of Southern Africa, Volume 54''], Ken Donaldson (Pty.) Limited, 1967, page 393</ref>\n\nFollowing the dissolution of the FBC in 1964, the government of Southern Rhodesia attempted to take control of RTV through the RBC, whose Chairman, J M Helliwell, announced that RBC would acquire all shares in RTV, \"at a price agreed upon by both parties\".<ref>[https://www.google.co.uk/search?hl=en&tbm=bks&q=%22Helliwell%22+%22at+a+price+agreed+upon+by+both+parties.%22&spell=1&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiYuIHZgoTpAhUVZxUIHZrbDyAQBQgnKAA&biw=1366&bih=625&dpr=1 ''Broadcasting''], Volume 68, Broadcasting Publications Incorporated, 1965, page 82</ref>   This prompted criticism by MPs, one of whom, Vernon Brelsford, moved a motion in the [[Southern Rhodesian Legislative Assembly|Legislative Assembly]] deploring the proposed acquisition.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=bFMOAQAAMAAJ&q=%22deplores+the+proposed+compulsory+acquisition+of+control+of+RTV%22&dq=%22deplores+the+proposed+compulsory+acquisition+of+control+of+RTV%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiquOa2p4LpAhVrURUIHVIBCtcQ6AEIKDAA ''Africa Diary''], Volume 5, M. Chhabra, 1964, page 2133</ref> He asked: \"Does it actually run the programmes to make sure that only its point of view is put over and no one else's is?\"<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=o2AtAAAAMAAJ&q=Rhodesian+Television+(RTV)&dq=Rhodesian+Television+(RTV)&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzn5KJpILpAhXsShUIHZa2CLQQ6AEIiQEwDQ ''The Mass Media in the Struggle for Zimbabwe: Censorship and Propaganda Under Rhodesian Front Rule''], Elaine Windrich, Mambo Press, 1981, page 35</ref> Prime Minister Ian Smith argued that control of television was necessary for \"winning the war for the minds of men\", and would save it from falling into the hands of \"communist sympathisers\".<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yjq1owYBF_kC&lpg=PA15&dq=rtv%20rhodesia&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q=rtv%20rhodesia&f=false ''Media, Public Discourse and Political Contestation in Zimbabwe''], Henning Melber, Nordic Africa Institute, 2004, page 15</ref>\n\nHowever, the government's move was rejected by RTV's directors.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=n8JYAAAAMAAJ&q=Rhodesian+Television+(RTV)&dq=Rhodesian+Television+(RTV)&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzn5KJpILpAhXsShUIHZa2CLQQ6AEIkAEwDg ''Africa Digest''], Volumes 12-14, Africa Publications Trust, 1964, page 97</ref> Instead, the RBC initially acquired a 51 per cent stake in the service, which became part of the RBC in 1976.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?ei=B0gYVaPOBo_3av2bgqgM&id=T7MsAAAAMAAJ&dq=rtv+rhodesia+south+africa+sabc+1976&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=actual+part ''Broadcasting: An Introduction''], John R. Bittner, Prentice-Hall International, 1980, page 263</ref> RBC TV was funded by advertising and a [[television licence fee]].<ref>[https://www.google.co.uk/search?tbm=bks&hl=en&q=%22RBC%27s+financial+support+comes+from+receiver+license+fees+and+advertising+revenue%22 ''Broadcasting in Africa: A Continental Survey of Radio and Television''], Sydney W. Head, Temple University Press, 1974, page 131</ref> Television reception was confined mainly to the large cities, and most viewers were [[Whites in Zimbabwe|whites]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G8cnAQAAIAAJ&q=rtv+rhodesia&dq=rtv+rhodesia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjl756a39HWAhWFL1AKHUQRAZYQ6AEILjAB''Censorship''], Volume 1, Congress for Cultural Freedom., 1964, page 29</ref> Umtali (now [[Mutare]]) only received television in 1972, by which time it was estimated that more than 90 per cent of the white population had access to the service.<ref name=\"Strack\" /> By 1973, RTV was broadcasting 42 hours a week from three transmitters, and 61 716 combined radio and television licences had been issued.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=V9fMDQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA536&dq=rhodesia%20television&pg=PA536#v=onepage&q=rhodesia%20television&f=false ''The Statesman's Year-Book 1976-77''], J. Paxton, page 536</ref>\n\n===Unilateral Declaration of Independence===\nIn 1965, the white minority government of [[Ian Smith]] issued a [[Unilateral Declaration of Independence (Rhodesia)|Unilateral Declaration of Independence]], under which censorship of broadcasting and the press was imposed, and key posts at the RBC were gradually filled by supporters of the ruling [[Rhodesian Front]] party.<ref name=\"Jones\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gDqsCQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA2713&dq=%22Rhodesian%20Broadcasting%20Corporation%22%20%22Director%20General%22&pg=PA2713#v=onepage&q=%22Rhodesian%20Broadcasting%20Corporation%22%20%22Director%20General%22&f=false ''Censorship: A World Encyclopedia''], Derek Jones, Routledge, 2001, page 2713</ref> The previous year, the Deputy Minister of Information, [[P. K. van der Byl]], described the aims of his Ministry as \"not merely to disseminate information from an interesting point of view but to play its part in fighting the propaganda battle on behalf of the country\".<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9jV1AAAAMAAJ&q=%22not+merely+to+disseminate+information+from+an+interesting+point+of+view+but+to+play+its+part+in+fighting+the+propaganda+battle+on+behalf+of+the+country%22&dq=%22not+merely+to+disseminate+information+from+an+interesting+point+of+view+but+to+play+its+part+in+fighting+the+propaganda+battle+on+behalf+of+the+country%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjUz7KTxq_MAhUkJcAKHW-UDj4Q6AEIHTAA ''Rhodesia: The Road to Rebellion''], James P. Barber, Institute of Race Relations, 1967, page 293</ref> In response, the RBC Director General, James Neill, resigned, citing political interference.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mXsjAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Rhodesian+Broadcasting+Corporation%22+%22Director+General%22&dq=%22Rhodesian+Broadcasting+Corporation%22+%22Director+General%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjK2p3xgtPWAhWLChoKHbZOCBoQ6AEIKDAA ''Combroad''], Issues 50-57, Commonwealth Broadcasting Association, 1981, page 60</ref>\n\nOn 1 January 1965, the RBC had ceased to relay the morning world news bulletin from the [[BBC]], and replaced it with a bulletin from the [[South African Broadcasting Corporation]] (SABC).<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dMgHAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22RBC%22+%22Rhodesia%22+%22BBC%22+%22SABC%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22In+fact%2C+the+morning+world+news+bulletin%2C+previously+relayed+from+the+BBC%2C+was+replaced+with+an+SABC+broadcast%22 ''The Journalist''], 1981, page 45</ref> However, afternoon and evening news relays of the BBC remained unchanged.<ref>[https://www.google.co.uk/search?q=On+1+January,+the+R.B.C.+discontinued+the+8+a.m.+news+relay+from+the+B.B.C.,+but+left+the+1+p.m.+and+6+p.m.+relays.+The+8+a.m.+relay+was+to+be+replaced+by+S.A.B.C.+news+relayed+from+Radio+South+Africa&num=30&rlz=1C1GGRV_enGB751GB751&source=lnms&tbm=bks&biw=1024&bih=662 ''News Letter''], Institute of Race Relations, London, 1965, page 23</ref>\n\nThe British government, which had denounced UDI as illegal, began broadcasting BBC programmes into Rhodesia by building a radio relay station in [[Francistown]], in the then [[Bechuanaland Protectorate]], now [[Botswana]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8bg8jQxkSTcC&lpg=PA111&dq=bbc%20rhodesia%20francistown&pg=PA111#v=onepage&q=bbc%20rhodesia%20francistown&f=false ''Botswana's Search for Autonomy in Southern Africa''], Richard Dale, Greenwood Publishing Group, 1995, page 111</ref> The Rhodesian government retaliated by clandestinely building a 400 000 watt transmitter nicknamed \"Big Bertha\", in order to jam the signal from the smaller BBC transmitter.<ref name=\"Africa Today\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=h89JAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Big+Bertha%22+Francistown&dq=%22Big+Bertha%22+Francistown&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjT2JGrj9PWAhVB1xoKHYZ6CTcQ6AEIKDAA ''Africa Today''], Volume 31, Africa Today Associates, 1984, page 46</ref> Programmes about Rhodesia were subjected to jamming, but other programmes were not affected.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0X_uILApgL0C&lpg=PA19&dq=bbc%20rhodesia%20francistown&pg=PA19#v=onepage&q=bbc%20rhodesia%20francistown&f=false ''Radio and Television Broadcasting on the European Continent''], Burton Paulu, University of Minnesota Press, 1967, page 19</ref> In 1968, the BBC ceased broadcasting from Francistown, and the relay station was transferred to the government of Botswana.<ref>[https://www.google.co.uk/search?tbm=bks&hl=en&q=%22BBC+closed+down+the+transmitter+and+handed+it+over+to+the+Botswana+government+in+1968%22 ''The Politics of International Telecommunications Regulation''], James G. Savage, Westview Press, 1989, page 134</ref>\n\nThe RBC operated two main services, the English-language General Service (or National Network),<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=633bAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Radio+Rhodesia%22&dq=%22Radio+Rhodesia%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjAztzbsNPWAhUKVRoKHZ3qBOEQ6AEIMTAC ''World Radio & TV Handbook''], Oluf Lund-Johansen, Cardfont Publishers under license from Billboard Publications., 1973,</ref> aimed at the white audience, and the African Service, broadcasting in English, Shona and Ndebele, aimed at black listeners. The RBC also established three community stations with a multi-racial audience, Radio Jacaranda (Salisbury), Radio Matopos (Bulawayo) and Radio Manica (Umtali).<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pLx1AAAAMAAJ&q=%22Radio+Jacaranda%22+%22RBC%22&dq=%22Radio+Jacaranda%22+%22RBC%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiz_5CzrdPWAhVK1BoKHfkDDxMQ6AEIKDAA ''Black List: The Concise and Comprehensive Reference Guide to Black Journalism, Radio, and Television, Educational and Cultural Organizations in the USA, Africa, and the Caribbean''], Volume 2, Black List, 1975, page 286</ref> In 1975, an [[Ndebele language (Zimbabwe)|Ndebele language]] service operating out of [[Bulawayo]], known as Radio Mthwakazi, was established, using the \"Big Bertha\" transmitter previously used to jam the BBC's broadcasts from Francistown.<ref>[https://www.google.co.uk/search?q=One+example+of+this+divide-and-rule+focus+in+broadcasting+was+the+setting+up+of+an+%27Ndebele+station%27+(Radio+Mthwakazi)+in+the+Bulawayo+area+in+1975,+utilizing+the+powerful+%27Big+Bertha%27+transmitter,+which+had+previously+been+used+to+jam+the&num=30&rlz=1C1GGRV_enGB751GB751&source=lnms&tbm=bks&biw=1024&bih=662 ''Broadcasting and Political Change in Zimbabwe 1931-1984''], James Joseph Zaffiro - 1984, page 74</ref>   \n   \nAs armed opposition to white minority rule mounted in the 1970s, Africans in Rhodesia increasingly began to turn to [[short wave]] radio broadcasts from neighbouring countries, which carried programmes from exiled nationalist movements, with the [[Zimbabwe African National Union (Patriotic Front)|Zimbabwe African National Union]]'s Voice of Zimbabwe operating from [[Mozambique]], and the rival [[Zimbabwe African People's Union]]'s Voice of the Revolution operating from [[Zambia]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uLenDhrLQ8oC&lpg=PA15&ots=3LG9ihNew5&dq=Zimbabwe%20African%20People's%20Union's%20Voice%20of%20the%20Revolution%20operating%20from%20Zambia.&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q=Zimbabwe%20African%20People's%20Union's%20Voice%20of%20the%20Revolution%20operating%20from%20Zambia.&f=false ''Making sense of cultural nationalism and the politics of commemoration under the Third Chimurenga in Zimbabwe''], Sabelo J. Ndlovu-Gatsheni and Wendy Willems, ''Journal of Southern African Studies'', 35 (4). pp. 945-965</ref>\n\nIn order to counter this, the RBC installed an [[FM broadcasting|FM]] network, while the government distributed FM-only receivers to chiefs and village headmen in the Tribal Trust Lands.<ref name=\"Africa Today\" /> It also ran campaigns promoting FM-only receivers, pointing out that they were exempt from the annual [[licence fee]], and how short wave broadcasts were affected by [[noise (radio)|static noise]] and required retuning between frequencies throughout the day.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=kpmyAAAAIAAJ&q=%22rhodesian+broadcasting+corporation%22+%22licence+fee%22&dq=%22rhodesian+broadcasting+corporation%22+%22licence+fee%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiN04PtgNPWAhXC1hoKHRqCD9sQ6AEIKDAA ''International Journal''], Volume 42, Canadian Institute of International Affairs, 1987, page 346</ref>\n\n===Transition to independence===\nIn 1979, following the adoption of a new constitution, Rhodesia was renamed [[Zimbabwe Rhodesia]], and in common with other state institutions which were renamed, the state broadcaster was renamed the Zimbabwe Rhodesia Broadcasting Corporation (ZRBC) under an amendment to the Broadcasting Act.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=a7cvAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&dq=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj518bbnYLpAhVORRUIHbw1D2gQ6AEIUTAF ''Namibia Papers: Working documents''], Issue 15, University of Bremen, Centre for African Studies/Namibia Project, page 178</ref> It also used the name \"Voice of Zimbabwe Rhodesia\" (VZR) on air.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uv0rAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&dq=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjztZrbmoLpAhX1t3EKHeM0B08Q6AEIXjAH ''Summary of World Broadcasts: Non-Arab Africa''], Issues 6082-6155, BBC, page 2</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rEIqAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Voice+of+Zimbabwe+Rhodesia%22&dq=%22Voice+of+Zimbabwe+Rhodesia%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi48cOJnYLpAhXVuXEKHQ6GBSwQ6AEIMDAB ''World Radio TV Handbook''], Billboard Publications, 1980, page 185</ref> In addition, the change of name saw the debut of Mandy Mundawarara, the country's first black television newsreader, whose father, Silas Mundawarara, had become Deputy Prime Minister in the government of [[Abel Muzorewa]].<ref name=\"WP1980\" />\n\nHowever, the Muzorewa government did not gain international recognition, and under the terms of the [[Lancaster House Agreement]], the country officially reverted to British rule as \"Southern Rhodesia\", with [[Christopher Soames, Baron Soames|Lord Soames]] as [[Governor of Southern Rhodesia|Governor]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=rTDvVo52tEAC&lpg=PA91&ots=RBUrvvu_Sa&dq=%22Constitution%20of%20Zimbabwe%20Rhodesia%22&pg=PA91#v=onepage&q=%22Constitution%20of%20Zimbabwe%20Rhodesia%22&f=true ''Collective Responses to Illegal Acts in International Law: United Nations Action in the Question of Southern Rhodesia''], Vera Gowlland-Debbas\nMartinus Nijhoff Publishers, 1990, page 91</ref> Despite this, the Corporation's name remained unchanged.<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1979/dec/17/zimbabwe-bill-1#S5LV0403P0_19791217_HOL_102 ZIMBABWE BILL], HL Deb 17 December 1979 vol 403 cc1470-514</ref> It was only on 28 March 1980, three weeks before independence, that \"Rhodesia\" was finally dropped from the Corporation's title.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=K2gEAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22+%22Zimbabwe+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&dq=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22+%22Zimbabwe+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjauuyumYLpAhX3SRUIHfBhADgQ6AEINzAC Broadcasting name change],''[[Herald (Zimbabwe)|The Herald]]'', March 29, 1980</ref> \n\nA number of other senior BBC staff were sent to the country to advise Lord Soames on election broadcasting, and also help the ZRBC with their preparations for independence.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1394002/Austen-Kark.html Obituary: Austen Kark], ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', 13 May 2002</ref> In the run-up to elections being held in February 1980, the Governor's Information Adviser held discussions with the ZRBC, leading the Election Commissioner agreed to a scheme to ensure that all parties standing in the elections should have equal free time on the public media.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jVENAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&dq=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiLjYrk5dLWAhWHNhoKHdZSBVIQ6AEIWjAK Southern Rhodesia: Independence Elections 1980: Report of the Election Commissioner Sir John Boynton, MC, Salisbury, March 1980], John K. Boynton, Great Britain. Foreign and Commonwealth Office, Her Majesty's Stationery Office, 1980, page 31</ref>\n\n==Post-independence==\n\n===Reorganisation of services===\nFollowing independence, radio services were reorganised, with three distinct networks being established: Radio One, the main English-language network, run by Africans but with some whites in key positions, Radio Two, combining the Harare and Radio Mthwakazi services and broadcasting in [[Shona language|Shona]] and [[Ndebele language (Zimbabwe)|Ndebele]], and Radio Three, replacing Radio Jacaranda.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-SMoAQAAMAAJ&q=Radio+Mthwakazi&dq=Radio+Mthwakazi&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4ovnCktPWAhXJmBoKHd-EAAMQ6AEITjAI ''Proceedings of the African Women's Features Services Workshop, Marandellas, Zimbabwe, 12-23 October, 1981''], UNESCO Regional Population Communication Unit for Africa, page 60</ref> Radio Four was established in 1982, as an educational channel.<ref name=\"Wells\" />\n\nThe legacy of [[Unilateral Declaration of Independence (Rhodesia)#British and international responses; sanctions|economic sanctions]] meant that ZBC inherited antiquated equipment with spares difficult to obtain, as manufacturers no longer produced [[black and white television]] transmission equipment.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=n4i2AAAAIAAJ&dq=%22Zimbabwe%22+%22TV%22++%22black+and+white%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22black+and+white+TV+transmission+equipment%22 ''Zimbabwe- The First Decade''], Elias Rusike, Roblaw Publishers, 1990, page 54</ref> In addition, the television service, now known as ZTV, only reached only 32 percent of the country's territory.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=proWAQAAMAAJ&q=%22ZTV+is+composed+of+one+black-and-white+TV+channel+which+covers+32+percent+of+the+country%27s+territory%22&dq=%22ZTV+is+composed+of+one+black-and-white+TV+channel+which+covers+32+percent+of+the+country%27s+territory%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEubvb0tHWAhVCZlAKHeXuBWIQ6AEIKDAA ''Country Market Survey''], Department of Commerce, Industry and Trade Administration., 1982, page 6</ref>\n\nThe conversion to [[colour television]] began in late 1982, using the [[PAL#PAL-B/G/D/K/I|PAL B]] system.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=b0kNAQAAMAAJ&q=%22conversion+of+the+black+and+white+television+service+to+colour+on+the+PAL+B+System%22&dq=%22conversion+of+the+black+and+white+television+service+to+colour+on+the+PAL+B+System%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEmL7z1tHWAhXRY1AKHWm2DakQ6AEIKDAA ''International TV & Video Guide''], Tantivy Press, 1985, page 204</ref> By this time, those with colour receivers could already watch imported programmes produced in colour.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QBMJAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Zimbabwe+Television%22+%22ZTV%22&dq=%22Zimbabwe+Television%22+%22ZTV%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj02bTosoLpAhUVVRUIHfvVAOAQ6AEIgwEwDA ''BM/E's World Broadcast News''], Broadband Information Services, 1982</ref> Colour transmissions were finally introduced in 1984.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?ei=nEsYVfK3MtbWavGogpAO&id=2MhBAAAAYAAJ&dq=zbc+tv+colour+1984&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Colour+transmission ''A Concise Encyclopedia of Zimbabwe''], Donatus Bonde, Mambo Press, 1988, page 410</ref> As much of the machinery had been in used for over two decades, and was now obsolete, it proved more economical to buy entirely new equipment than to replace it.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6xwxAQAAIAAJ&q=%22the+old+black-and-white+machinery%22&dq=%22the+old+black-and-white+machinery%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiC-Miq1NHWAhVFmbQKHcK2ANIQ6AEIKDAA ''Africa Calls from Zimbabwe''], Issues 131-138, Africa Calls Publishers, 1982, page 22</ref> A second television channel, available only in [[Harare]],<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rkm7AAAAIAAJ&dq=%22Zimbabwe+Broadcasting+Corporation%22+%22second%22+%22TV%22+%22channel%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Harare+area%22 ''Children and Women in Zimbabwe: A Situation Analysis, Update 1994''], Unicef, 1994, page 40</ref> was introduced in 1986.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pDwIAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22Zimbabwe+Broadcasting+Corporation%22+%22second%22+%22TV%22+%22channel%22+%221986%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22In+1986%2C+ZBC+installed+a+second+channel%22 ''Africa Film & TV''], Z Promotions, 2001, page 217</ref>\n\nIn a reflection of the news [[ZANU PF]] government's political leanings, [[Robert Mugabe]], previously described only as \"a terrorist leader\", was now described as \"[[Prime Minister of Zimbabwe|Comrade Prime Minister]]\".<ref name=\"WP1980\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1980/06/01/zimbabwes-news-media-change-tune-under-black-rule/b67c6c36-b778-41c0-8db2-db1b61b30b7d/ Zimbabwe's News Media Change Tune Under Black Rule], ''[[Washington Post]]'', June 1, 1980</ref> In addition, most of the white staff left ZBC after independence, and many of the black staff who replaced them had previously worked in for radio services operated by the nationalist movements from exile in [[Zambia]] and [[Mozambique]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TMX3_raXHDcC&lpg=PA143&dq=zbc%20monopoly%201997&pg=PA143#v=onepage&q&f=false The dual legacy of democracy and authoritarianism], Helge Ronning and Tawana Kupe, in ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TMX3_raXHDcC&lpg=PA143&dq=zbc%20monopoly%201997&pg=PA138#v=onepage&q&f=false De-Westernizing Media Studies]'', editors James Curran, Myung-Jin Park, Routledge, 5 Jul 2005, page 138</ref>\n\n===Local programming===\nAt independence, 30 per cent of television programming was locally produced.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xQBbVfPukGMC&lpg=PA51&dq=zbc%20tv%20programme%20imports%2030%20per%20cent%20local&pg=PA51#v=onepage&q=zbc%20tv%20programme%20imports%2030%20per%20cent%20local&f=false ''Zimbabwe's Cinematic Arts: Language, Power, Identity''], Katrina Daly Thompson, Indiana University Press, 2013, page 51</ref> By late 1982, local programmes accounted for 40 per cent of output.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=AiAoAQAAMAAJ&q=%22colour+television%22+ZBC&dq=%22colour+television%22+ZBC&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjmleip69TWAhUSalAKHbZ1BkIQ6AEIRjAH ''Report of Second Meeting of Monitoring Group on Follow-up to Intergovernmental Conference on Communication Policies in Africa: Harare, Zimbabwe, 26-29 October 1982''], AFRICOM Monitoring Group. Meeting, United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization, 1982, page 9</ref> While some programming was in Shona and Ndebele, 80 per cent of programming was in English, of which most was imported, mainly from the US, Britain and Australia.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rkm7AAAAIAAJ&dq=zbc+tv+programme+imports+africa&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Most+of+these%2C+except+for+news+and+current+affairs+programmes%2C+are+imported+British%2C+Australian%2C+or+American+shows%22 ''Children and Women in Zimbabwe: A Situation Analysis, Update 1994''], Unicef 1994, page 41</ref> Despite this reliance on foreign content, in the 1980s, the locally produced drama ''The Mukadota Family'' became the most popular programme in the country.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0KIR8RucnDYC&lpg=PA41&dq=mukadota%20family&pg=PA41#v=onepage&q=mukadota%20family&f=false ''How \"American\" Is Globalization?''], William Marling, JHU Press, 2006, page 41</ref>\n\nAs the 1957 Broadcasting Act remained in force, ZBC inherited RBC's state monopoly on broadcasting, remaining accountable to the country's Minister of Information.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uRZDAQAAIAAJ&q=zbc+monopoly+broadcasting+act+1957&dq=zbc+monopoly+broadcasting+act+1957&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjExo3r7tXWAhWLmbQKHetqD6IQ6AEIQzAF ''Media, democracy and development''], Elin W. Andersen, Dept. of Media and Communication, University of Oslo, 1997, page 10</ref> Expressing his dislike of independent broadcasting in 1995, [[Robert Mugabe]], by now [[President of Zimbabwe|President]], remarked \"you do not know what propaganda a non-state radio station might broadcast\".<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FBEmAQAAIAAJ&q=%22you+do+not+know+what+propaganda+a+non-state+radio+station+might+broadcast%22&dq=%22you+do+not+know+what+propaganda+a+non-state+radio+station+might+broadcast%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjBmZfonqnfAhUwSN8KHST5Av8Q6AEIKjAA ''Critical Analysis of the Media Law in Zimbabwe''], Nkosi Ndlela, Media Institute of Southern Africa. Zimbabwe Chapter, Konrad Adenauer Foundation, 2003, page 44</ref> However, the [[Government of Zimbabwe|government]] announced that the ZBC monopoly on broadcasting would be abolished by the end of 1997.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PcEULjohrUC&lpg=PA396&ots=NZTm-75_hY&dq=zbc%20monopoly&pg=PA396#v=onepage&q=zbc%20monopoly&f=false Zimbabwe], \u00d8yvind Thiis and Geoff Feltoe, in [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PcEULjohrUC&dq=zbc+monopoly&source=gbs_navlinks_s ''International Human Rights in Developing Countries Yearbook 1997''], editors Hugo Stokke, Astri Suhrke, Arne Tostensen, Martinus Nijhoff Publishers, 1998, page 396</ref>\n\nAs a result, the ZBC's second TV channel was discontinued and replaced by Joy TV, the country's first independent channel, which operated on a lease agreement with the ZBC.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ypFWqOJFKPEC&pg=PA58&lpg=PA58&dq=joy+tv+zimbabwe&source=bl&ots=fX0tP1X4ZL&sig=m7JorC7v1hYI5bUA0C9YoBmKyXY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=0k4YVfvUHIGtPZiGgLAH&ved=0CG0Q6AEwDQ#v=onepage&q=joy%20tv%20zimbabwe&f=true ''Culture and Customs of Zimbabwe''], Oyekan Owomoyela, Greenwood Publishing Group, 2002, page 58</ref> This channel lasted until 2002, when it was controversially taken off the air for allegedly violating the Broadcasting Services Act.<ref>[http://www.pambazuka.net/en/category.php/media/8085 Zimbabwe: CURTAIN COMES DOWN ON JOY TV], ''Pambazuka'', 6 June 2001</ref>\n\n===Accusations of pro-government bias===\nIn 2015, [[Freedom House]] described ZBC coverage as overwhelmingly favouring the ruling [[ZANU-PF]].<ref>[https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-press/2016/zimbabwe Zimbabwe Freedom of the Press], [[Freedom House]], 2016</ref> In 2003, a study conducted by the Media Monitoring Project of Zimbabwe (MMPZ) in 2003 showed that one of the propaganda jingles, ''Rambai Makashinga'' or \"Continue Persevering\", was being played 288 times a day on the four ZBC radio stations, and 72 times a day on ZBC television.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LJbFniZhtDQC&lpg=PA81&dq=Zimbabwe%20Broadcasting%20Corporation%20censorship&pg=PA81#v=onepage&q=Zimbabwe%20Broadcasting%20Corporation%20censorship&f=false ''Zimbabwe: A Survey''], African Minds, 2009, page 81</ref>\n\n==Radio==\nZBC has six radio networks, which are;\n*[[ZBC National FM| National FM]] -  broadcasting news and current affairs in [[Languages of Zimbabwe| various indigenous languages]],<ref>[http://www.nationalfm.co.zw/ National FM]</ref>\n*[[Radio Zimbabwe]] - broadcasts only in [[Shona language|Shona]] and [[Northern Ndebele language|Ndebele]],<ref>[http://www.radiozim.co.zw/ Radio Zimbabwe]</ref>\n*[[Power FM Zimbabwe| Power Fm]] (formerly Radio 3 / 3FM) - broadcasting pop music,<ref>[http://www.powerfm.co.zw/ Power FM]</ref>\n*[[Classic 263]] (formerly Spot FM or SFM) - carrying sports, news and current affairs <ref>[http://www.classic263.co.zw/ Classic 263]</ref>\n*[[Khulumani FM]] - station designed for the metropolitan province of [[Bulawayo]] and [[Matabeleland]] region <ref>[http://www.khulumanifm.co.zw/ Khulumani FM]</ref>\n*[[95.8 Central Radio]] - broadcasting for [[Gweru]] <ref>[http://www.centralradio.co.zw/ Central Radio]</ref>.\n\nLocal radio stations run hourly news bulletins which range from two minutes to the longest being a ten-minute bulletin on weekends and holidays. Presenters include, Admire Mhungu, Innocent Manyenga, Memory Chamisa and Keith Mawoyo.\n\nOn the national languages desk readers include Nqobile Malinga, Patience Machokoto, Taboka Ncube, Faith Nare, Lucy Ngosolo and Caroline Sithole. Bulletins come out live on Classic 263 at 7 am, 8 am, 1 pm, 6 pm and 8 pm and running from Monday to Friday. The anchors are Nomalanga Vuma, Theophilus Chuma, Ian Zvoma, Butler Nhepure and Jonathan Marerwa.\n\n==Television==\nZBC's television service now consists of a single channel, known as [[ZBC TV]]. The ZBC re-established a second TV channel of its own, Channel 2, in April 2010,<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201004130289.html Zimbabwe: ZBC to Launch Channel Two], ''[[The Herald (Zimbabwe)|The Herald]]'', 13 April 2010</ref> but this station was decommissioned in August 2015.<ref>[https://www.dailynews.co.zw/articles/2015/08/12/zbc-fires-hundreds-closes-tv-station ZBC fires hundreds, closes TV station], ''[[Daily News (Zimbabwe)|Daily News]]'', 12 August 2015</ref>\n\nNews bulletins include the morning ''Good Morning Zimbabwe'', produced by Admire Mhungu, lunchtime news, ''Nhau Indaba'' and ''News Hour''.<ref>[http://www.zbc.co.zw/?option=com_content&view=article&id=546&Itemid=99  ZBC-TV Programme Line Up]</ref> Rumbidzai Takawira, the anchor, is usually the host of ''News Hour''.\n\n''[[Battle Of The Chefs Harare|Battle of the Chefs]]'' is one of the first food-related reality TV shows to air on ZBC.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Media of Zimbabwe]]\n* [[Communications in Zimbabwe]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.zbc.co.zw ZBC]\n\n[[Category:1980 establishments in Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Media in Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Publicly funded broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Multilingual broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1980]]\n[[Category:Television in Zimbabwe]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox broadcasting network\n| network_name =  (ZBC) {{in lang|en}}|\nnetwork_logo = [[File:Zimbabwe Broadcasting Corporation (logo).jpg|150px|Logo of the ZBC]]\n| country      = [[Zimbabwe]]\n| network_type = [[Television network]] <br /> [[Radio network]]\n| available    = National <br /> Worldwide\n| owner        = [[Government of Zimbabwe]]\n| launch_date  = 1963 (as Rhodesian Broadcasting Corporation)\n| past_names   = Rhodesian Broadcasting Corporation, and later <br /> Zimbabwe Rhodesian Broadcasting Corporation\n| website      = http://www.zbc.co.zw\n}}\n\nThe '''Zimbabwe Broadcasting Corporation '''('''ZBC''') is the state-controlled broadcaster in [[Zimbabwe]]. It was established as the '''Rhodesian Broadcasting Corporation''' ('''RBC'''), taking its current name in 1980. Like the RBC before it, the ZBC has been accused of being a [[government mouthpiece]] with no [[editorial independence]].<ref>[http://www.theindependent.co.zw/2012/02/16/muckraker-zbc-has-taken-over-the-rbcs-mantle/ 'MuckRaker: ZBC has taken over the RBC's mantle'], ''[[Zimbabwe Independent]]'', 16 February 2012</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Introduction of radio===\nRadio was first introduced in the then [[Southern Rhodesia]] in 1933, in Belvedere in Salisbury (now [[Harare]]) by [[Imperial Airways]], which was used to provide radio guidance and weather reports.<ref name=\"Wells\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZgptYdAcsOgC&lpg=PA159&dq=zbc%20radio%204&pg=PA159#v=onepage&q&f=false ''World Broadcasting: A Comparative View''], Alan Wells, Greenwood Publishing Group, 1996, pages 157-159</ref> However, it was not until 1941 that the first professional broadcaster was established.<ref name=\"survey\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LJbFniZhtDQC&lpg=PA10&dq=%22Southern%20Rhodesia%22%20%22radio%22%201933&pg=PA10#v=onepage&q=%22Southern%20Rhodesia%22%20%22radio%22%201933&f=false ''Zimbabwe: A Survey''], African Minds, 2009, page 10</ref> This was known as the Central African Broadcasting Service (CABS) and had responsibility for broadcasting in [[Northern Rhodesia]] (now [[Zambia]]) and [[Nyasaland]] (now [[Malawi]]) as well as Southern Rhodesia.<ref name=\"Wells\" />\n\nFollowing the creation of the [[Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland]] in 1953, a new organisation was established on 1 February 1958, known as the Federal Broadcasting Corporation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland (FBC).<ref name=\"handbook\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DnFHAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22Federal+Broadcasting+Corporation+of+Rhodesia+and+Nyasaland%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Federal+Broadcasting+Corporation%22 ''Handbook to the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland''], Rhodesia and Nyasaland, Federal Information Dept, William Vernon Brelsford, Cassell, 1960, page 552</ref> However, CABS continued to operate as a radio station aimed at African audiences.<ref name=\"Wells\" /> When the Federation was dissolved in 1963, the FBC was disbanded, and each territory acquired its own broadcasting service, which in Southern Rhodesia was initially known as the Southern Rhodesian Broadcasting Corporation (SRBC).<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ht7iAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Southern+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&dq=%22Southern+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjjoIrJrILpAhUWSxUIHfP0BCIQ6AEIXjAH ''Guide to Southern Africa''], 1965, page 249</ref> This later became known as the Rhodesian Broadcasting Corporation (RBC).<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4FDjAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Southern+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&dq=%22Southern+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjjoIrJrILpAhUWSxUIHfP0BCIQ6AEIfDAL ''Standard Encyclopaedia of Southern Africa''], Volume 10, NASOU, 1974, page 132</ref>\n\n===Introduction of television===\n[[ZBC TV| Television]] was introduced on 14 November 1960, first in [[Harare|Salisbury]], with transmissions in [[Bulawayo]] beginning seven months later.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5sZBAQAAIAAJ&dq=rhodesia+television+rtv+1960&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=welensky ''EBU Review: Programmes, Administration, Law, Volume 71''], Administrative Office of the European Broadcasting Union, 1962, page 12</ref> It was only the second such service in sub-Saharan Africa after Nigeria,<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xQBbVfPukGMC&pg=PA32&lpg=PA32&dq=rtv+rhodesia&source=bl&ots=26f1qRRMdU&sig=1yTPAweyK_qpt8hnFGDMLsW4nM0&hl=en&sa=X&ei=zjoYVcHYCcfYPeW1gZgC&ved=0CFkQ6AEwCw#v=onepage&q=rtv%20rhodesia&f=true ''Zimbabwe's Cinematic Arts: Language, Power, Identity''], Katrina Daly Thompson, Indiana University Press, 2013, page 32</ref> and the first such service in southern Africa, as [[South Africa]] did not [[Television in South Africa#Opposition to introduction|introduce television]] until 1976.<ref name=\"Strack\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ZVt0AAAAMAAJ&dq=south+africa+TV+1976+rhodesia&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Without+television+until+1976%22 ''Sanctions: The Case of Rhodesia''], Harry R. Strack, Syracuse University Press, 1978,\n page 235</ref>\n\nIt was initially operated by a private company, Rhodesian Television (RTV) on behalf of the then FBC, with its major shareholder being [[South Africa]]n companies, including the [[Cape Argus|Argus Group]] of newspapers, through its subsidiary, the Rhodesian Printing and Publishing Company, and also served [[Northern Rhodesia]] until its independence as [[Zambia]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QadAAAAAIAAJ&dq=Rhodesian%20Television%20(RTV)&pg=PA255#v=onepage&q=Rhodesian%20Television%20(RTV)&f=false ''Area Handbook for Zambia''], Volume 550, Issue 75, Irving Kaplan, American University (Washington, D.C.). Foreign Area Studies\nU.S. Government Printing Office, 1969, page 255</ref> Other companies included Davenport and Meyer,<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HrXVAAAAMAAJ&dq=rhodesia+television+rtv&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22rhodesian+television%22+ ''Viewing the Foreign and the Local in Zimbabwe: Film, Television, and the Shona Viewers''], Katrina Daly Thompson\nUniversity of Wisconsin--Madison, 2004, page 125</ref> the latter of which operated [[LM Radio]], based in [[Mozambique]], then under [[Portuguese Mozambique|Portuguese rule]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G2dmAAAAMAAJ&q=%22davenport+and+meyer%22+lm+radio&dq=%22davenport+and+meyer%22+lm+radio&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiM-JPHwfPKAhXlQpoKHYGHD7oQ6AEIIDAA ''Who's who of Southern Africa, Volume 54''], Ken Donaldson (Pty.) Limited, 1967, page 393</ref>\n\nFollowing the dissolution of the FBC in 1964, the government of Southern Rhodesia attempted to take control of RTV through the RBC, whose Chairman, J M Helliwell, announced that RBC would acquire all shares in RTV, \"at a price agreed upon by both parties\".<ref>[https://www.google.co.uk/search?hl=en&tbm=bks&q=%22Helliwell%22+%22at+a+price+agreed+upon+by+both+parties.%22&spell=1&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiYuIHZgoTpAhUVZxUIHZrbDyAQBQgnKAA&biw=1366&bih=625&dpr=1 ''Broadcasting''], Volume 68, Broadcasting Publications Incorporated, 1965, page 82</ref>   This prompted criticism by MPs, one of whom, Vernon Brelsford, moved a motion in the [[Southern Rhodesian Legislative Assembly|Legislative Assembly]] deploring the proposed acquisition.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=bFMOAQAAMAAJ&q=%22deplores+the+proposed+compulsory+acquisition+of+control+of+RTV%22&dq=%22deplores+the+proposed+compulsory+acquisition+of+control+of+RTV%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiquOa2p4LpAhVrURUIHVIBCtcQ6AEIKDAA ''Africa Diary''], Volume 5, M. Chhabra, 1964, page 2133</ref> He asked: \"Does it actually run the programmes to make sure that only its point of view is put over and no one else's is?\"<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=o2AtAAAAMAAJ&q=Rhodesian+Television+(RTV)&dq=Rhodesian+Television+(RTV)&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzn5KJpILpAhXsShUIHZa2CLQQ6AEIiQEwDQ ''The Mass Media in the Struggle for Zimbabwe: Censorship and Propaganda Under Rhodesian Front Rule''], Elaine Windrich, Mambo Press, 1981, page 35</ref> Prime Minister Ian Smith argued that control of television was necessary for \"winning the war for the minds of men\", and would save it from falling into the hands of \"communist sympathisers\".<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yjq1owYBF_kC&lpg=PA15&dq=rtv%20rhodesia&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q=rtv%20rhodesia&f=false ''Media, Public Discourse and Political Contestation in Zimbabwe''], Henning Melber, Nordic Africa Institute, 2004, page 15</ref>\n\nHowever, the government's move was was rejected by RTV's directors.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=n8JYAAAAMAAJ&q=Rhodesian+Television+(RTV)&dq=Rhodesian+Television+(RTV)&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjzn5KJpILpAhXsShUIHZa2CLQQ6AEIkAEwDg ''Africa Digest''], Volumes 12-14, Africa Publications Trust, 1964, page 97</ref> Instead, the RBC initially acquired a 51 per cent stake in the service, which became part of the RBC in 1976.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?ei=B0gYVaPOBo_3av2bgqgM&id=T7MsAAAAMAAJ&dq=rtv+rhodesia+south+africa+sabc+1976&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=actual+part ''Broadcasting: An Introduction''], John R. Bittner, Prentice-Hall International, 1980, page 263</ref> RBC TV was funded by advertising and a [[television licence fee]].<ref>[https://www.google.co.uk/search?tbm=bks&hl=en&q=%22RBC%27s+financial+support+comes+from+receiver+license+fees+and+advertising+revenue%22 ''Broadcasting in Africa: A Continental Survey of Radio and Television''], Sydney W. Head, Temple University Press, 1974, page 131</ref> Television reception was confined mainly to the large cities, and most viewers were [[Whites in Zimbabwe|whites]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G8cnAQAAIAAJ&q=rtv+rhodesia&dq=rtv+rhodesia&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjl756a39HWAhWFL1AKHUQRAZYQ6AEILjAB''Censorship''], Volume 1, Congress for Cultural Freedom., 1964, page 29</ref> Umtali (now [[Mutare]]) only received television in 1972, by which time it was estimated that more than 90 per cent of the white population had access to the service.<ref name=\"Strack\" /> By 1973, RTV was broadcasting 42 hours a week from three transmitters, and 61 716 combined radio and television licences had been issued.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=V9fMDQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA536&dq=rhodesia%20television&pg=PA536#v=onepage&q=rhodesia%20television&f=false ''The Statesman's Year-Book 1976-77''], J. Paxton, page 536</ref>\n\n===Unilateral Declaration of Independence===\nIn 1965, the white minority government of [[Ian Smith]] issued a [[Unilateral Declaration of Independence (Rhodesia)|Unilateral Declaration of Independence]], under which censorship of broadcasting and the press was imposed, and key posts at the RBC were gradually filled by supporters of the ruling [[Rhodesian Front]] party.<ref name=\"Jones\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gDqsCQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA2713&dq=%22Rhodesian%20Broadcasting%20Corporation%22%20%22Director%20General%22&pg=PA2713#v=onepage&q=%22Rhodesian%20Broadcasting%20Corporation%22%20%22Director%20General%22&f=false ''Censorship: A World Encyclopedia''], Derek Jones, Routledge, 2001, page 2713</ref> The previous year, the Deputy Minister of Information, [[P. K. van der Byl]], described the aims of his Ministry as \"not merely to disseminate information from an interesting point of view but to play its part in fighting the propaganda battle on behalf of the country\".<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9jV1AAAAMAAJ&q=%22not+merely+to+disseminate+information+from+an+interesting+point+of+view+but+to+play+its+part+in+fighting+the+propaganda+battle+on+behalf+of+the+country%22&dq=%22not+merely+to+disseminate+information+from+an+interesting+point+of+view+but+to+play+its+part+in+fighting+the+propaganda+battle+on+behalf+of+the+country%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjUz7KTxq_MAhUkJcAKHW-UDj4Q6AEIHTAA ''Rhodesia: The Road to Rebellion''], James P. Barber, Institute of Race Relations, 1967, page 293</ref> In response, the RBC Director General, James Neill, resigned, citing political interference.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mXsjAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Rhodesian+Broadcasting+Corporation%22+%22Director+General%22&dq=%22Rhodesian+Broadcasting+Corporation%22+%22Director+General%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjK2p3xgtPWAhWLChoKHbZOCBoQ6AEIKDAA ''Combroad''], Issues 50-57, Commonwealth Broadcasting Association, 1981, page 60</ref>\n\nOn 1 January 1965, the RBC had ceased to relay the morning world news bulletin from the [[BBC]], and replaced it with a bulletin from the [[South African Broadcasting Corporation]] (SABC).<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=dMgHAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22RBC%22+%22Rhodesia%22+%22BBC%22+%22SABC%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22In+fact%2C+the+morning+world+news+bulletin%2C+previously+relayed+from+the+BBC%2C+was+replaced+with+an+SABC+broadcast%22 ''The Journalist''], 1981, page 45</ref> However, afternoon and evening news relays of the BBC remained unchanged.<ref>[https://www.google.co.uk/search?q=On+1+January,+the+R.B.C.+discontinued+the+8+a.m.+news+relay+from+the+B.B.C.,+but+left+the+1+p.m.+and+6+p.m.+relays.+The+8+a.m.+relay+was+to+be+replaced+by+S.A.B.C.+news+relayed+from+Radio+South+Africa&num=30&rlz=1C1GGRV_enGB751GB751&source=lnms&tbm=bks&biw=1024&bih=662 ''News Letter''], Institute of Race Relations, London, 1965, page 23</ref>\n\nThe British government, which had denounced UDI as illegal, began broadcasting BBC programmes into Rhodesia by building a radio relay station in [[Francistown]], in the then [[Bechuanaland Protectorate]], now [[Botswana]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8bg8jQxkSTcC&lpg=PA111&dq=bbc%20rhodesia%20francistown&pg=PA111#v=onepage&q=bbc%20rhodesia%20francistown&f=false ''Botswana's Search for Autonomy in Southern Africa''], Richard Dale, Greenwood Publishing Group, 1995, page 111</ref> The Rhodesian government retaliated by clandestinely building a 400 000 watt transmitter nicknamed \"Big Bertha\", in order to jam the signal from the smaller BBC transmitter.<ref name=\"Africa Today\">[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=h89JAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Big+Bertha%22+Francistown&dq=%22Big+Bertha%22+Francistown&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjT2JGrj9PWAhVB1xoKHYZ6CTcQ6AEIKDAA ''Africa Today''], Volume 31, Africa Today Associates, 1984, page 46</ref> Programmes about Rhodesia were subjected to jamming, but other programmes were not affected.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0X_uILApgL0C&lpg=PA19&dq=bbc%20rhodesia%20francistown&pg=PA19#v=onepage&q=bbc%20rhodesia%20francistown&f=false ''Radio and Television Broadcasting on the European Continent''], Burton Paulu, University of Minnesota Press, 1967, page 19</ref> In 1968, the BBC ceased broadcasting from Francistown, and the relay station was transferred to the government of Botswana.<ref>[https://www.google.co.uk/search?tbm=bks&hl=en&q=%22BBC+closed+down+the+transmitter+and+handed+it+over+to+the+Botswana+government+in+1968%22 ''The Politics of International Telecommunications Regulation''], James G. Savage, Westview Press, 1989, page 134</ref>\n\nThe RBC operated two main services, the English-language General Service (or National Network),<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=633bAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Radio+Rhodesia%22&dq=%22Radio+Rhodesia%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjAztzbsNPWAhUKVRoKHZ3qBOEQ6AEIMTAC ''World Radio & TV Handbook''], Oluf Lund-Johansen, Cardfont Publishers under license from Billboard Publications., 1973,</ref> aimed at the white audience, and the African Service, broadcasting in English, Shona and Ndebele, aimed at black listeners. The RBC also established three community stations with a multi-racial audience, Radio Jacaranda (Salisbury), Radio Matopos (Bulawayo) and Radio Manica (Umtali).<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pLx1AAAAMAAJ&q=%22Radio+Jacaranda%22+%22RBC%22&dq=%22Radio+Jacaranda%22+%22RBC%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiz_5CzrdPWAhVK1BoKHfkDDxMQ6AEIKDAA ''Black List: The Concise and Comprehensive Reference Guide to Black Journalism, Radio, and Television, Educational and Cultural Organizations in the USA, Africa, and the Caribbean''], Volume 2, Black List, 1975, page 286</ref> In 1975, an [[Ndebele language (Zimbabwe)|Ndebele language]] service operating out of [[Bulawayo]], known as Radio Mthwakazi, was established, using the \"Big Bertha\" transmitter previously used to jam the BBC's broadcasts from Francistown.<ref>[https://www.google.co.uk/search?q=One+example+of+this+divide-and-rule+focus+in+broadcasting+was+the+setting+up+of+an+%27Ndebele+station%27+(Radio+Mthwakazi)+in+the+Bulawayo+area+in+1975,+utilizing+the+powerful+%27Big+Bertha%27+transmitter,+which+had+previously+been+used+to+jam+the&num=30&rlz=1C1GGRV_enGB751GB751&source=lnms&tbm=bks&biw=1024&bih=662 ''Broadcasting and Political Change in Zimbabwe 1931-1984''], James Joseph Zaffiro - 1984, page 74</ref>   \n   \nAs armed opposition to white minority rule mounted in the 1970s, Africans in Rhodesia increasingly began to turn to [[short wave]] radio broadcasts from neighbouring countries, which carried programmes from exiled nationalist movements, with the [[Zimbabwe African National Union (Patriotic Front)|Zimbabwe African National Union]]'s Voice of Zimbabwe operating from [[Mozambique]], and the rival [[Zimbabwe African People's Union]]'s Voice of the Revolution operating from [[Zambia]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uLenDhrLQ8oC&lpg=PA15&ots=3LG9ihNew5&dq=Zimbabwe%20African%20People's%20Union's%20Voice%20of%20the%20Revolution%20operating%20from%20Zambia.&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q=Zimbabwe%20African%20People's%20Union's%20Voice%20of%20the%20Revolution%20operating%20from%20Zambia.&f=false ''Making sense of cultural nationalism and the politics of commemoration under the Third Chimurenga in Zimbabwe''], Sabelo J. Ndlovu-Gatsheni and Wendy Willems, ''Journal of Southern African Studies'', 35 (4). pp. 945-965</ref>\n\nIn order to counter this, the RBC installed an [[FM broadcasting|FM]] network, while the government distributed FM-only receivers to chiefs and village headmen in the Tribal Trust Lands.<ref name=\"Africa Today\" /> It also ran campaigns promoting FM-only receivers, pointing out that they were exempt from the annual [[licence fee]], and how short wave broadcasts were affected by [[noise (radio)|static noise]] and required retuning between frequencies throughout the day.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=kpmyAAAAIAAJ&q=%22rhodesian+broadcasting+corporation%22+%22licence+fee%22&dq=%22rhodesian+broadcasting+corporation%22+%22licence+fee%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiN04PtgNPWAhXC1hoKHRqCD9sQ6AEIKDAA ''International Journal''], Volume 42, Canadian Institute of International Affairs, 1987, page 346</ref>\n\n===Transition to independence===\nIn 1979, following the adoption of a new constitution, Rhodesia was renamed [[Zimbabwe Rhodesia]], and in common with other state institutions which were renamed, the state broadcaster was renamed the Zimbabwe Rhodesia Broadcasting Corporation (ZRBC) under an amendment to the Broadcasting Act.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=a7cvAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&dq=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj518bbnYLpAhVORRUIHbw1D2gQ6AEIUTAF ''Namibia Papers: Working documents''], Issue 15, University of Bremen, Centre for African Studies/Namibia Project, page 178</ref> It also used the name \"Voice of Zimbabwe Rhodesia\" (VZR) on air.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uv0rAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&dq=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjztZrbmoLpAhX1t3EKHeM0B08Q6AEIXjAH ''Summary of World Broadcasts: Non-Arab Africa''], Issues 6082-6155, BBC, page 2</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rEIqAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Voice+of+Zimbabwe+Rhodesia%22&dq=%22Voice+of+Zimbabwe+Rhodesia%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi48cOJnYLpAhXVuXEKHQ6GBSwQ6AEIMDAB ''World Radio TV Handbook''], Billboard Publications, 1980, page 185</ref> In addition, the change of name saw the debut of Mandy Mundawarara, the country's first black television newsreader, whose father, Silas Mundawarara, had become Deputy Prime Minister in the government of [[Abel Muzorewa]].<ref name=\"WP1980\" />\n\nHowever, the Muzorewa government did not gain international recognition, and under the terms of the [[Lancaster House Agreement]], the country officially reverted to British rule as \"Southern Rhodesia\", with [[Christopher Soames, Baron Soames|Lord Soames]] as [[Governor of Southern Rhodesia|Governor]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=rTDvVo52tEAC&lpg=PA91&ots=RBUrvvu_Sa&dq=%22Constitution%20of%20Zimbabwe%20Rhodesia%22&pg=PA91#v=onepage&q=%22Constitution%20of%20Zimbabwe%20Rhodesia%22&f=true ''Collective Responses to Illegal Acts in International Law: United Nations Action in the Question of Southern Rhodesia''], Vera Gowlland-Debbas\nMartinus Nijhoff Publishers, 1990, page 91</ref> Despite this, the Corporation's name remained unchanged.<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/1979/dec/17/zimbabwe-bill-1#S5LV0403P0_19791217_HOL_102 ZIMBABWE BILL], HL Deb 17 December 1979 vol 403 cc1470-514</ref> It was only on 28 March 1980, three weeks before independence, that \"Rhodesia\" was finally dropped from the Corporation's title.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=K2gEAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22+%22Zimbabwe+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&dq=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22+%22Zimbabwe+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjauuyumYLpAhX3SRUIHfBhADgQ6AEINzAC Broadcasting name change],''[[Herald (Zimbabwe)|The Herald]]'', March 29, 1980</ref> \n\nA number of other senior BBC staff were sent to the country to advise Lord Soames on election broadcasting, and also help the ZRBC with their preparations for independence.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1394002/Austen-Kark.html Obituary: Austen Kark], ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', 13 May 2002</ref> In the run-up to elections being held in February 1980, the Governor's Information Adviser held discussions with the ZRBC, leading the Election Commissioner agreed to a scheme to ensure that all parties standing in the elections should have equal free time on the public media.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jVENAQAAIAAJ&q=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&dq=%22Zimbabwe+Rhodesia+Broadcasting+Corporation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiLjYrk5dLWAhWHNhoKHdZSBVIQ6AEIWjAK Southern Rhodesia: Independence Elections 1980: Report of the Election Commissioner Sir John Boynton, MC, Salisbury, March 1980], John K. Boynton, Great Britain. Foreign and Commonwealth Office, Her Majesty's Stationery Office, 1980, page 31</ref>\n\n==Post-independence==\n\n===Reorganisation of services===\nFollowing independence, radio services were reorganised, with three distinct networks being established: Radio One, the main English-language network, run by Africans but with some whites in key positions, Radio Two, combining the Harare and Radio Mthwakazi services and broadcasting in [[Shona language|Shona]] and [[Ndebele language (Zimbabwe)|Ndebele]], and Radio Three, replacing Radio Jacaranda.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-SMoAQAAMAAJ&q=Radio+Mthwakazi&dq=Radio+Mthwakazi&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4ovnCktPWAhXJmBoKHd-EAAMQ6AEITjAI ''Proceedings of the African Women's Features Services Workshop, Marandellas, Zimbabwe, 12-23 October, 1981''], UNESCO Regional Population Communication Unit for Africa, page 60</ref> Radio Four was established in 1982, as an educational channel.<ref name=\"Wells\" />\n\nThe legacy of [[Unilateral Declaration of Independence (Rhodesia)#British and international responses; sanctions|economic sanctions]] meant that ZBC inherited antiquated equipment with spares difficult to obtain, as manufacturers no longer produced [[black and white television]] transmission equipment.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=n4i2AAAAIAAJ&dq=%22Zimbabwe%22+%22TV%22++%22black+and+white%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22black+and+white+TV+transmission+equipment%22 ''Zimbabwe- The First Decade''], Elias Rusike, Roblaw Publishers, 1990, page 54</ref> In addition, the television service, now known as ZTV, only reached only 32 percent of the country's territory.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=proWAQAAMAAJ&q=%22ZTV+is+composed+of+one+black-and-white+TV+channel+which+covers+32+percent+of+the+country%27s+territory%22&dq=%22ZTV+is+composed+of+one+black-and-white+TV+channel+which+covers+32+percent+of+the+country%27s+territory%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEubvb0tHWAhVCZlAKHeXuBWIQ6AEIKDAA ''Country Market Survey''], Department of Commerce, Industry and Trade Administration., 1982, page 6</ref>\n\nThe conversion to [[colour television]] began in late 1982, using the [[PAL#PAL-B/G/D/K/I|PAL B]] system.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=b0kNAQAAMAAJ&q=%22conversion+of+the+black+and+white+television+service+to+colour+on+the+PAL+B+System%22&dq=%22conversion+of+the+black+and+white+television+service+to+colour+on+the+PAL+B+System%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEmL7z1tHWAhXRY1AKHWm2DakQ6AEIKDAA ''International TV & Video Guide''], Tantivy Press, 1985, page 204</ref> By this time, those with colour receivers could already watch imported programmes produced in colour.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QBMJAQAAMAAJ&q=%22Zimbabwe+Television%22+%22ZTV%22&dq=%22Zimbabwe+Television%22+%22ZTV%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj02bTosoLpAhUVVRUIHfvVAOAQ6AEIgwEwDA ''BM/E's World Broadcast News''], Broadband Information Services, 1982</ref> Colour transmissions were finally introduced in 1984.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?ei=nEsYVfK3MtbWavGogpAO&id=2MhBAAAAYAAJ&dq=zbc+tv+colour+1984&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Colour+transmission ''A Concise Encyclopedia of Zimbabwe''], Donatus Bonde, Mambo Press, 1988, page 410</ref> As much of the machinery had been in used for over two decades, and was now obsolete, it proved more economical to buy entirely new equipment than to replace it.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6xwxAQAAIAAJ&q=%22the+old+black-and-white+machinery%22&dq=%22the+old+black-and-white+machinery%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiC-Miq1NHWAhVFmbQKHcK2ANIQ6AEIKDAA ''Africa Calls from Zimbabwe''], Issues 131-138, Africa Calls Publishers, 1982, page 22</ref> A second television channel, available only in [[Harare]],<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rkm7AAAAIAAJ&dq=%22Zimbabwe+Broadcasting+Corporation%22+%22second%22+%22TV%22+%22channel%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Harare+area%22 ''Children and Women in Zimbabwe: A Situation Analysis, Update 1994''], Unicef, 1994, page 40</ref> was introduced in 1986.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pDwIAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22Zimbabwe+Broadcasting+Corporation%22+%22second%22+%22TV%22+%22channel%22+%221986%22&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22In+1986%2C+ZBC+installed+a+second+channel%22 ''Africa Film & TV''], Z Promotions, 2001, page 217</ref>\n\nIn a reflection of the news [[ZANU PF]] government's political leanings, [[Robert Mugabe]], previously described only as \"a terrorist leader\", was now described as \"[[Prime Minister of Zimbabwe|Comrade Prime Minister]]\".<ref name=\"WP1980\">[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1980/06/01/zimbabwes-news-media-change-tune-under-black-rule/b67c6c36-b778-41c0-8db2-db1b61b30b7d/ Zimbabwe's News Media Change Tune Under Black Rule], ''[[Washington Post]]'', June 1, 1980</ref> In addition, most of the white staff left ZBC after independence, and many of the black staff who replaced them had previously worked in for radio services operated by the nationalist movements from exile in [[Zambia]] and [[Mozambique]].<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TMX3_raXHDcC&lpg=PA143&dq=zbc%20monopoly%201997&pg=PA143#v=onepage&q&f=false The dual legacy of democracy and authoritarianism], Helge Ronning and Tawana Kupe, in ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=TMX3_raXHDcC&lpg=PA143&dq=zbc%20monopoly%201997&pg=PA138#v=onepage&q&f=false De-Westernizing Media Studies]'', editors James Curran, Myung-Jin Park, Routledge, 5 Jul 2005, page 138</ref>\n\n===Local programming===\nAt independence, 30 per cent of television programming was locally produced.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xQBbVfPukGMC&lpg=PA51&dq=zbc%20tv%20programme%20imports%2030%20per%20cent%20local&pg=PA51#v=onepage&q=zbc%20tv%20programme%20imports%2030%20per%20cent%20local&f=false ''Zimbabwe's Cinematic Arts: Language, Power, Identity''], Katrina Daly Thompson, Indiana University Press, 2013, page 51</ref> By late 1982, local programmes accounted for 40 per cent of output.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=AiAoAQAAMAAJ&q=%22colour+television%22+ZBC&dq=%22colour+television%22+ZBC&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjmleip69TWAhUSalAKHbZ1BkIQ6AEIRjAH ''Report of Second Meeting of Monitoring Group on Follow-up to Intergovernmental Conference on Communication Policies in Africa: Harare, Zimbabwe, 26-29 October 1982''], AFRICOM Monitoring Group. Meeting, United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization, 1982, page 9</ref> While some programming was in Shona and Ndebele, 80 per cent of programming was in English, of which most was imported, mainly from the US, Britain and Australia.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rkm7AAAAIAAJ&dq=zbc+tv+programme+imports+africa&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Most+of+these%2C+except+for+news+and+current+affairs+programmes%2C+are+imported+British%2C+Australian%2C+or+American+shows%22 ''Children and Women in Zimbabwe: A Situation Analysis, Update 1994''], Unicef 1994, page 41</ref> Despite this reliance on foreign content, in the 1980s, the locally produced drama ''The Mukadota Family'' became the most popular programme in the country.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0KIR8RucnDYC&lpg=PA41&dq=mukadota%20family&pg=PA41#v=onepage&q=mukadota%20family&f=false ''How \"American\" Is Globalization?''], William Marling, JHU Press, 2006, page 41</ref>\n\nAs the 1957 Broadcasting Act remained in force, ZBC inherited RBC's state monopoly on broadcasting, remaining accountable to the country's Minister of Information.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uRZDAQAAIAAJ&q=zbc+monopoly+broadcasting+act+1957&dq=zbc+monopoly+broadcasting+act+1957&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjExo3r7tXWAhWLmbQKHetqD6IQ6AEIQzAF ''Media, democracy and development''], Elin W. Andersen, Dept. of Media and Communication, University of Oslo, 1997, page 10</ref> Expressing his dislike of independent broadcasting in 1995, [[Robert Mugabe]], by now [[President of Zimbabwe|President]], remarked \"you do not know what propaganda a non-state radio station might broadcast\".<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FBEmAQAAIAAJ&q=%22you+do+not+know+what+propaganda+a+non-state+radio+station+might+broadcast%22&dq=%22you+do+not+know+what+propaganda+a+non-state+radio+station+might+broadcast%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjBmZfonqnfAhUwSN8KHST5Av8Q6AEIKjAA ''Critical Analysis of the Media Law in Zimbabwe''], Nkosi Ndlela, Media Institute of Southern Africa. Zimbabwe Chapter, Konrad Adenauer Foundation, 2003, page 44</ref> However, the [[Government of Zimbabwe|government]] announced that the ZBC monopoly on broadcasting would be abolished by the end of 1997.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PcEULjohrUC&lpg=PA396&ots=NZTm-75_hY&dq=zbc%20monopoly&pg=PA396#v=onepage&q=zbc%20monopoly&f=false Zimbabwe], \u00d8yvind Thiis and Geoff Feltoe, in [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PcEULjohrUC&dq=zbc+monopoly&source=gbs_navlinks_s ''International Human Rights in Developing Countries Yearbook 1997''], editors Hugo Stokke, Astri Suhrke, Arne Tostensen, Martinus Nijhoff Publishers, 1998, page 396</ref>\n\nAs a result, the ZBC's second TV channel was discontinued and replaced by Joy TV, the country's first independent channel, which operated on a lease agreement with the ZBC.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ypFWqOJFKPEC&pg=PA58&lpg=PA58&dq=joy+tv+zimbabwe&source=bl&ots=fX0tP1X4ZL&sig=m7JorC7v1hYI5bUA0C9YoBmKyXY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=0k4YVfvUHIGtPZiGgLAH&ved=0CG0Q6AEwDQ#v=onepage&q=joy%20tv%20zimbabwe&f=true ''Culture and Customs of Zimbabwe''], Oyekan Owomoyela, Greenwood Publishing Group, 2002, page 58</ref> This channel lasted until 2002, when it was controversially taken off the air for allegedly violating the Broadcasting Services Act.<ref>[http://www.pambazuka.net/en/category.php/media/8085 Zimbabwe: CURTAIN COMES DOWN ON JOY TV], ''Pambazuka'', 6 June 2001</ref>\n\n===Accusations of pro-government bias===\nIn 2015, [[Freedom House]] described ZBC coverage as overwhelmingly favouring the ruling [[ZANU-PF]].<ref>[https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-press/2016/zimbabwe Zimbabwe Freedom of the Press], [[Freedom House]], 2016</ref> In 2003, a study conducted by the Media Monitoring Project of Zimbabwe (MMPZ) in 2003 showed that one of the propaganda jingles, ''Rambai Makashinga'' or \"Continue Persevering\", was being played 288 times a day on the four ZBC radio stations, and 72 times a day on ZBC television.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=LJbFniZhtDQC&lpg=PA81&dq=Zimbabwe%20Broadcasting%20Corporation%20censorship&pg=PA81#v=onepage&q=Zimbabwe%20Broadcasting%20Corporation%20censorship&f=false ''Zimbabwe: A Survey''], African Minds, 2009, page 81</ref>\n\n==Radio==\nZBC has six radio networks, which are;\n*[[ZBC National FM| National FM]] -  broadcasting news and current affairs in [[Languages of Zimbabwe| various indigenous languages]],<ref>[http://www.nationalfm.co.zw/ National FM]</ref>\n*[[Radio Zimbabwe]] - broadcasts only in [[Shona language|Shona]] and [[Northern Ndebele language|Ndebele]],<ref>[http://www.radiozim.co.zw/ Radio Zimbabwe]</ref>\n*[[Power FM Zimbabwe| Power Fm]] (formerly Radio 3 / 3FM) - broadcasting pop music,<ref>[http://www.powerfm.co.zw/ Power FM]</ref>\n*[[Classic 263]] (formerly Spot FM or SFM) - carrying sports, news and current affairs <ref>[http://www.classic263.co.zw/ Classic 263]</ref>\n*[[Khulumani FM]] - station designed for the metropolitan province of [[Bulawayo]] and [[Matabeleland]] region <ref>[http://www.khulumanifm.co.zw/ Khulumani FM]</ref>\n*[[95.8 Central Radio]] - broadcasting for [[Gweru]] <ref>[http://www.centralradio.co.zw/ Central Radio]</ref>.\n\nLocal radio stations run hourly news bulletins which range from two minutes to the longest being a ten-minute bulletin on weekends and holidays. Presenters include, Admire Mhungu, Innocent Manyenga, Memory Chamisa and Keith Mawoyo.\n\nOn the national languages desk readers include Nqobile Malinga, Patience Machokoto, Taboka Ncube, Faith Nare, Lucy Ngosolo and Caroline Sithole. Bulletins come out live on Classic 263 at 7 am, 8 am, 1 pm, 6 pm and 8 pm and running from Monday to Friday. The anchors are Nomalanga Vuma, Theophilus Chuma, Ian Zvoma, Butler Nhepure and Jonathan Marerwa.\n\n==Television==\nZBC's television service now consists of a single channel, known as [[ZBC TV]]. The ZBC re-established a second TV channel of its own, Channel 2, in April 2010,<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201004130289.html Zimbabwe: ZBC to Launch Channel Two], ''[[The Herald (Zimbabwe)|The Herald]]'', 13 April 2010</ref> but this station was decommissioned in August 2015.<ref>[https://www.dailynews.co.zw/articles/2015/08/12/zbc-fires-hundreds-closes-tv-station ZBC fires hundreds, closes TV station], ''[[Daily News (Zimbabwe)|Daily News]]'', 12 August 2015</ref>\n\nNews bulletins include the morning ''Good Morning Zimbabwe'', produced by Admire Mhungu, lunchtime news, ''Nhau Indaba'' and ''News Hour''.<ref>[http://www.zbc.co.zw/?option=com_content&view=article&id=546&Itemid=99  ZBC-TV Programme Line Up]</ref> Rumbidzai Takawira, the anchor, is usually the host of ''News Hour''.\n\n''[[Battle Of The Chefs Harare|Battle of the Chefs]]'' is one of the first food-related reality TV shows to air on ZBC.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Media of Zimbabwe]]\n* [[Communications in Zimbabwe]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.zbc.co.zw ZBC]\n\n[[Category:1980 establishments in Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Media in Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Publicly funded broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Multilingual broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1980]]\n[[Category:Television in Zimbabwe]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zimbabwe_Broadcasting_Corporation"}
